animal.description:
IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING DANCER, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE FACEBOOK PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Hi my name is Dancer! I’m a 2 year old  terrier mix. My momma Allie was a stray on the streets of Detroit and gave birth to me and 5 other pups out in the bitter cold, but MADR scooped her up along with us babies and literally saved our lives! If it wasn't for MADR we would have froze to death. 

I am happy to do anything my humans are doing. I love to play catch, lay next to my foster, chase squirrels and follow my foster around the house. I love treats and peanut butter!! I am a very affectionate guy once I get to know you. I am selective on which dogs I like. I lived with cats when I was younger. I would do best with children 15 years old and older. My forever home is required to have a fenced yard where I can safely run and play. I am neutered, my vaccinations are up to date, I take heartworm preventative every month as well as being house and crate trained. I am a great, guy who loves to have fun, go on adventures and yearns to be part of a forever family.

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year old to attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters.  Dancer's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
Sam is a 3-year-old Golden Retriever mix. Sam has to have a 6 Foot privacy fence. He can sometimes be apprehensive of strangers, but is easily won over with the right approach. He's super affectionate, loves attention, is playful, and will lay at your feet anytime you need him to chill out with you. Sam's ideal home would be with one or several calm, confident adults. Sam likes to play fetch and play in a fenced yard. He can be a challenge to walk when he sees other dogs or critters. Sam has shared a home with a dog and done ok but it takes slow introductions. Sam is vocal and cannot be adopted to a family living in an apartment or condo with close neighbors. Sam has worked with a few trainers and his new family would need to continue to his training. If you are an approved adopter and are interested in Sam, please contact Jeanine or Lynette. If you are not yet approved but live in SW or Central Florida, please visit www.grrswf.org and fill out an application.

If you are interested in learning more about a GRRSWF dog, please contact us at applications@grrswf.org, or you can read about our adoption process in detail and download an application from our website at http://www.grrswf.org/index-2.html

PLEASE NOTE: We serve Southwest Florida from Naples to Ocala. If you live OUTSIDE of our service area and are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please note that we will only consider an application for senior dogs (over the age of 8) or dogs with special needs (usually medication). BEFORE submitting your application, send an email to info@GRRSWF.org to request an exception to our service area. If that approval is given, you will be asked to complete an application, clearly stating on it that you are interested in a special needs or senior dog. However, please be aware that, unfortunately, there are some locations we simply cannot cover because we do not have sufficient representation in those areas to perform the required home visits prior to the adoption, or follow-up visits afterward. If that is the case, we will be happy to refer you to a local rescue or shelter.

animal.description:
Update 12-12-20:
Our apologies for slow responses!! We have been having multiple difficulties and are way behind responding to our inquiries. We will be trying to catch up over the next two weeks. Suzy is still available and we will be reviewing and responding to her inquiries as soon as possible.  Thanks for your patience! Email is our only communication at the moment.

PLEASE READ BELOW IF INTERESTED IN THIS DOG! 

IF YOU ARE SEEING THIS LISTING, THEN THE DOG IS STILL AVAILABLE AND WE ARE PROCESSING INQUIRIES FOR ITS NEW HOME. We remove them immediately once we have stopped taking inquiries and have a pending home.

PLEASE FOLLOW THE DIRECTIONS BELOW TO BE CONSIDERED. Please provide a contact phone number! Once we narrow down to the top three candidates, we usually call them to discuss details and then make our choice to meet the dog. Those who send no information about your home or family, or just ask is the dog available, how much, or how old will not be answered. All of that information is listed here and unfortunately, due to the volume of inquiries asking those basic questions, we are unable to answer all of the emails and texts. We also get a lot of people who send in the basic question because of the cute factor and really are not ready to adopt yet.  Please make sure that all of your household members are ready to adopt before pursuing adoption.

We understand that some of this is due to the new Petfinder format with their basic question at the bottom and apologize for that. In addition we are getting duplicates from most people because of confusion with Petfinder's new system which is making it difficult to tell if your inquiry was sent to us. Also the Petfinder new system asks for a zip code or location but does not forward that to us so we cannot tell your location. We do not fly our animals so please make sure that you are able to drive to Michigan if you are interested in one of our pets.  We are getting a lot of complaints from prospective homes trying to navigate Petfinder's new system and requests from several who enjoyed the various sections of our previous home page.  We cannot do anything about the changes to the format and the removal of the information on our home page, etc. Many people are simply sending their information to us directly at petangels@gmail.com or via text or voicemail to 734-645-7705 which may be a simpler solution at this point.

We do our best to place our adoptable animals within 1 to 2 weeks if they are ready to go and qualified homes are available. 

 Please make sure ALL members of your family are in agreement to welcome a new dog to your family and you are ready to meet when you contact us. Thank you for your cooperation so these babies don't continue to grow up in their foster homes and bond to those families.

We may make our initial contact via text or email but our final candidates will be called when we are making our final decision.  If you have inquired and not provided a phone number yet, please provide one at 734-645-7705.

  If you are just seeing the listing and are interested, please feel free to go ahead and inquire and tell us why you think the pup is a good fit and what it's life would be like if it joins your family. We will take down the listing as soon as the pup is in its new home.

Update 2: 6-11-20:

We are behind and apologize for the slow responses! We will be making calls for Suzy Friday and/or Saturday and hopefully setting her up a meet and greet soon. Thanks for your patience.

2-2-20 Update:
FINALLY got some pictures of this girl!

Posted 2-12-19:

Pictures will be added as soon as we get some good ones but she is camera shy and a fast runner.

Suzy is starting her search for her forever home.  She is estimated to be 7-8 years old although she acts more like 3 to 4 and is very agile! 

We aren't sure of her breed mix but are thinking maybe feist with rat terrier or beagle or something. She is about 25 pounds and has a slender head and pointed nose.

She is a medium to high energy dog and loves to run and play with other dogs. She is shy at first with humans but follows you around once she's comfortable. 

She is very food motivated and we are working on basic commands. She is a very intelligent dog.

She has no vet history and is not spayed yet. She will be starting from scratch.

She is beginning crate training and we are evaluating her housebreaking skills.

If interested in adopting, please call or text 734-645-7705 and leave your name, location, brief summary of family, work hours, dog experience, training and exercise plans, and a phone contact number. 

Adoption fee is $250 (Cash with receipt). If she is not spayed by the time her family finds her, she may be allowed to go to her home on a signed spay agreement to be completed within 30 days at a reduced adoption fee.

If you would like to take me home please complete a Pet Adoption Application

male. 60 lbs. click name to read morePRE-APPROVED application is required to meet Spike. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY

Background: Transfer

Personality: Needs slow intros but very affectionate and easy going once he bonds

Cats: No

Dogs: No, accept for Honey(who he came in with)

Kids: 16 and older

Energy Level: Medium

Housebroken: Yes

Crate Trained: Yes

Prey drive for Wildlife(no invisible fence if high) High

Fence required: No

Best home for this Pet: I likey Spikey(as he is lovingly referred to by staff)should go to a family with bully breed experience. Spike requires multiple meets(by appt) so he can get to know you before going home. He would like an easy going low traffic home that will exercise him daily, as he enjoys being out and about. He can be a little strong on the leash but is well mannered and he really enjoys having his nose to the ground to take in all the scents

Spike requires multi meets.

We do our best to get to know each and every dog at our camp. Their personalities emerge after being with us for a bit and sometimes change. The personality and other information included in the above description is based on what we know currently in the shelter environment. All dogs are up to date on vaccines (Distemper, Rabies, Bordetella), microchipped, spayed/neutered and receive worming, flea & tick medication before they are adopted out. Please note there are some exceptions depending on the condition of the dog. If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application at https://www.camppapillon.org/dog-application.

Once your dog is in your home, they will adjust and relax and could become more playful or show more personality traits as they begin to open up. Once adopted, please allow your dog time to decompress and relax in a stable home environment.

animal.description: Beans is a 14 year old pug who loves 3 things: eating, sleeping, and eating again. He came to PugHearts a tad overweight at 26 pounds, but he has shed 2 pounds so far. He loves soft toys and is quite the character. Beans has had successful surgery to rid him of bladder stones, so he must stay on a restrictive diet to avoid a re-occurrence. He also has an old injury to his left eye and has no vision in it. Beans is a sedentary fellow who is happy with a low key lifestyle. He is happiest when he knows where you are and will especially follow you if you make your way into the kitchen....his favorite room. Beans sleeps in his own bed and is house trained. He gets along with other dogs and ignores the cat. Mr. Beans, as I refer to him, is a total sweetheart who is looking for a quiet home for his retirement years.

animal.description:
Hi! I’m a good boy, yes I am! My name is Charlie Boy, and I’d like to be your outdoor adventure buddy. It’s my favorite thing in the world, I mean other than belly rubs, and I have excellent leash manners. I’m about 4 years old and my foster fam says I’m 50 pounds of pure puppy-love. I love everybody, especially other doggies (any age, any size!). I’m good at playing like a li’l dog around li’l dogs, and like a big dog around big dogs. I’m not sure about cats but maybe a calm, dog savvy feline would be cool.

Even though I’m high-energy on the trail, I can be quiet around the house and cuddly with people I trust. It takes me a little time to warm up to new folks; when I was little, I was left out in a yard all the time and ignored – me and almost 70 other dogs. I might need to sniff and retreat a few times but I’m more than willing to do a drive by, and once we’re friends, we’re BEST FRIENDS.

My perfect home would include a playful dog-sibling (or several), a private yard for zoomies, toys to play with, balls to chase, and lots of hikes with my people! I really appreciate exercise but don’t worry if you can’t take me out, I’ll still be a good boy. I’m hoping for a family of patient, active adults, a quiet and child-free environment, and did I mention doggie friends? And belly rubs please. Do you give good belly rubs and like to get outdoors? Then I’m your boy!

Southern California adopters only please!

animal.description:
Meet Axel a young Great Pyrenees who had a hard life before coming into rescue. He was kept chained with little shelter and no human interaction and was abandoned when his owners moved. He has not let that stop him and is thriving in his foster home! If you are looking for that typical Pyrenees personality, look no further as Axel is your boy. He takes his job as guard dog very seriously and insists on doing the full perimeter check every night, sleeps by the door to ward off any intruders, and loves to lay outside. Axel loves to play with all the female foster dogs in his home and even ignores the small ones when they bark at him. His foster mom says he gets a perplexed look on his face as if he is trying to figure out what that little five pound furball is barking at :) Axel is housebroken, rides great in a car, and walks nicely on a leash. He is the full package...has a Pyrfect personality, gets along with every dog he meets, is good with cats, and loves people. Axel would love a home with other dogs to play with, and a family who will love him for the rest of his days!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY.  View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

Max is by nature a working dog. His breed is one that flourishes with constant exercise and activities that stimulate his mind and body. He does well with other confident dogs that are leaders and not submissive. His human adopters must have the following qualities to be considered: Strong, dominant leaders who will continue obedience courses as well as enroll him in additional courses such as agility training.

We are only considering active families who enjoy and participate in outdoor sports and activities that will include Max in all their fun and adventure such as camping, hiking, etc. The person or family has a social lifestyle where Max can interact with a variety of people and other dogs. Will be willing to have assessments by our trainer to make sure that Max’s training regimen is on track, so that he will not revert back to his nervous state, and feed him high quality and healthy food that is specifically designed for an active and young dog. 

If you are looking for a dog that fits Max’s description and feel you would be a good fit, please fill out an adoption questionnaire on the Forte Animal Rescue website.

animal.description:
Meet Star! Star is a 5 year old Pointer mix. Star is a super sweet girl. She is house trained and does well with older kids. She needs an active family that keep her busy and exercised. Star needs a home with NO cats, and this pretty little lady prefers the company of male dogs only. If you would like to make this sweet girl a part of your family, fill out an application at www.barktownrescue.org.
STAR'S ADOPTION FEE IS $150The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the dog's predominant breed or breed mix. We strongly encourage you to select your new pet by looking at each dog's individual personality and pet qualities rather than relying on a breed label that is only our best guess.

Our adoption fees vary from $150 and up. All of our dogs are up to date on vaccines, heart worm preventives, and flea/tick medication, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Portions of your adoption fee also help care for the sick and injured animals that we take in. Thank you for supporting us and considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
My name is Ren and I am a mix of Chihuahua and Dachshund or MinPin. Whatever I am, I have been told I’m cute. I am about two years old and my coloring is brown. 

I was in a hoarding situation with way too many dogs, and so I haven’t had a good start in life. I am very mistrustful when you first meet me because of my past living situation. When I first arrived at my foster home, I didn’t go near anyone. But my foster mom kept picking me up and having me sit in her lap while she petted me. That was kind of nice, and now I go sit by her on my own and I have even crawled in her lap!

Strangers are frightening, but my foster mom is working with me to teach me that not all people are bad or scary. If you adopt me, you will have to be patient with me. I want to learn to love and trust, but it will take time. My foster mom says your patience with me will be well worth it because I am a sweet boy. My vaccinations are all up to date and I am working on being fully housetrained. I am also neutered.

You can meet me or learn more about me by contacting JAN at crazy4mutts@outlook.com. I’m being fostered in the El Cajon area of San Diego County.

Diva is 11 years old and weighs 8 lbs.  Diva came to us as a confiscate because of cruelty.  She came into Animal Control with 2 other dogs that she lived with.  Diva is good with other dogs and cats but is leary of people.  She is not a cuddler, but we think in time she could be.  Diva wants to warm up to people but is not sure of them.  We think with the right family she will learn to trust.  She comes by foster mom and likes to be petted and have her butt scratched but she still does not like to be held.  Foster mom picks her up in a towel but she is not happy about it. Diva is getting a dental on January 6 and will be available after that.   Diva needs a special loving home

animal.description: Darwin is available to take your "cool factor" to the next level, friends. This guy is "cool" personified. We discovered Darwin at Fulton Animal Services, where he took our breath away. At 4, he's a XL lab-mystery mix guy who is just stunning in person. He was adopted for a few months but recently came back to PAWS Atlanta, where we're hoping to find a better fit for him. Darwin's one challenge lately is that he has shown some resource guarding tendencies around food. This is common and can usually be corrected with some consistent training. We can help get you both on the right track and put you in touch with some excellent resources in the area. Because of the food guarding issue, we want Darwin to go to an adult home, preferably one where he can get some daily exercise and activities that will challenge his mind. We are crazy about this sweet lug and would love to tell you more about Darwin. Come by and take him out for a walk on our trail.

animal.description:
If you are looking for 100 lbs of lap dog, then you absolutely have to meet our guy Jake, a 3 year old super nice Pyr mix. This sweet boy is a big fan of snuggles and cuddles and just about anything else he gets to do with his people. Jake has flourished with love and attention since being in his foster home. He is a completely different pupper than the skinny scared guy who first came into rescue. Jake is now extremely outgoing, curious, and loving. He’s very gentle in all situation and patient when it comes to waiting for his turn at treat time. Jake also loves hanging out with dogs, and is great with all size pups from tiny to extra large. But at the end of the day, his favorite place is wherever his human family members are. He REALLY enjoys any and all attention. In fact, if you even look at him long enough he will melt like butter at your feet with all paws in the air and a belly ready for rubs! His foster mom says he LOVES LOVES LOVES to cuddle and has the most adorable soft snore. Just like meeting new people, Jake has never met a snack he doesn’t like :) And as far as looks go, Jake definitely stands out in a crowd. Between those beautiful markings, one shorter ear, and that super expressive face, he’s nearly irresistible. Being food motivated helps with training and so far he walks well using his harness, has mastered the sit command, and is crate trained (he's also learned lots of new tricks including a kangaroo impression). Jake is just an all around love and would bring years of joy to any family who opens their home to him - his foster wants to see him adopted to a home that will love him as much as they do!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
loving and affectionateThis is beautiful Bella!

Bella is a 4 1/2 year old, American Staffordshire Terrier mix. Bella is vetted, potty trained, she's silly and perfection in the home. She loves exploring on walks and chasing after little bunnies. She's smart, very loyal, and loves car rides.

She has been in a few foster homes since we rescued her from Carson shelter a couple years ago. Her ideal home would be quiet, where she can bask in the sun, enjoy her yard, love on her humans and be the center of attention. She does need to be the only dog, since that's where she's happiest.

Bella is a gorgeous pup who is affectionate and just amazing. She has the sweetest disposition and is a total love. Bella is looking for a forever home and a family she can love and protect. If you think she would be a great addition to your pack, please submit a completed application a www.doggiebonez.com, so that we can schedule a meet and greet. She is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short and/or long term doggie foster families. We greatly appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort and safety of a home and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if needed) etc. If you are interested please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
Video: https://youtu.be/jCzTji3X224

**SPONSORED ADOPTION FEE*
Briggs is one of our longer term adoptables, but that doesn't mean that he isn't a phenomenal dog. Briggs does have some separation anxiety issues, but is a lovable dog that doesn't know a stranger. He was a shelter favorite, and is a volunteer favorite at Peace. He comes with his adoption fee SPONSORED, and 3 training sessions in his new home to help ensure that the transition is as smooth as possible. Please give Briggs a second glance. He may just be the perfect guy for your home! <3

Briggs, Big Dave, Mushy Face, has been with us since February and we aren't sure why he hasn't received much interest! He is 3-4 years old and a bigger boy, at approximately 75-80 pounds. We don't see any problems with this though, because there is just more to love!

And love he does. Briggs is incredibly people friendly. As big and intimidating as he may look, he is the type of dog to approach a stranger with a full body wag and kisses. All he wants in life is all the pats and butt scritchies. His big ol' head is perfect for smushing and head pets.

He is dog friendly and was a playgroup rock star! He currently lives splendidly with a female pit in his foster home. He can get a little excited when he's unable to greet another dog, but he is easily redirected! He is a big, friendly guy and just wants to meet all the people and dogs. He is child friendly, and generally very affectionate. Apply to adopt him today!

ABOUT PEACE 4 PITS RESCUE:
Please note that we do not have a facility or shelter where you can view adoptables. We are a foster-based rescue in Chicago-land, which means that each dog is placed with a family in the area. This allows us to better understand each dog's individual personalities. 

You must complete an application before you can schedule a meet and greet with each animal. The application can be found here: http://peaceforpits.org/adoptionfoster-application/ or if you prefer a Word version, download it here: https://goo.gl/bKo84P and email it to p4papplications@gmail.com. Our adoption fee is typically $350 for an adult dog, and $400 for a dog under one year. It includes all vetting and spay/neuter.

animal.description:
Hi everyone!!  JOJO here!!  I’m about 5 1/2 years young, and still have oodles of energy!!  I’m a white with gray spots pittie mix, some people might consider me a bit of a low rider, whatever, I have the best personality!!  I weigh about 55 lbs, and am super athletic, (if I do say so myself).  I love to be active, am very energetic I love all humans, but because of my exuberance it’s probably best that I go to a home with kiddos 12 and up.  
Now as much as I love, love all humans, I don’t feel the same way about the feline species, so no cats please.  I like male dogs, but I can be selective, (what self-respecting female isn’t??) so please let’s do a proper meet and greet!
I’m house trained, crate trained and clicker trained….whew, that’s a lot of training!!  But it goes to show you how smart I am!!
Not to brag, but…..I of course know sit, stay,  down, paw….I can touch a target, “look at me”, walking gently on a leash, jumping over ~1 foot obstacles, and of course climbing up ramp obstacles, I can stay in a sit, give paw or run right up and down…whatever you tell me to do. Have you seen my pictures on top of the ramp?  You know not every dog will even go up them….just sayin’ ?
 I really am a quick study and I so want to please you….
Do you have room in your home and heart for me?  By the way, I’m super duper soft….and would love to snuggle with you! Remember, you can find me at the Heart of the Catskills, Delhi NY….I’m waiting anxiously for you…please try to hurry!!
All my love and kisses, JOJO

animal.description:
Last Weigh-in: 51 lbs

Foster updates:
Uma will do well in a home with older children and without other dogs. 

“Uma is happy and loving. Coy! Always down for cuddles and pets. In love with her crate. Puts herself to bed every night at approximately 9:30pm... unless she’s in a party mood. Uma has not been tested with cats or children yet.

Uma is extremely affectionate and meeting new people is her favorite thing in the world. She is constantly itching for human companionship and would sit in your lap and give you kisses all day if you’d let her. She listens well, is very eager to please and is typically very gentle and calm but also gets excited for walks outside. Sadly, she hasn’t always been treated well by humans and she will cower at sudden movements or loud noises. However, she is getting more confident with each day and with each new person she meets who show her only affection. It’s incredible how a dog who was treated so poorly by people can still love them so much!”

Uma is Crate Trained, Leash trained, Slightly active, Does well in a car, Likes toys, Obedient, Playful, Affectionate, Goofy & Gentle

-----------------------------------

Uma’s Story
 For several years, I was owned by some men, used as a breeding dog, and tethered in a backyard.  I've had a pup companion named Ethan for a while now (he's my best friend and a new Streetdog too!) But that was the only life I ever known. Last September, I stopped receiving food from my ""owners"" because they didn't want to pay for it anymore, and I withered away to almost nothing. I had laid down in the hot sun and became very weak. I nearly decided that it was my time to go, but some people were passing by, approached me, and brought me food and water. They began visiting me everyday for months to try to gain my trust. I stayed as far as I could, because I didn't know that humans could be kind, but slowly, day by day, they always came back. They always spoke kindly to me, they always brought food, some toys and even some blankets when it started getting cold.  

 A few weeks ago, the lights in the house that I "belonged to" got shut off for good and all signs of "my owners" were gone. I had been abandoned officially. But the neighbors kept coming and kept visiting.  They started searching for rescue help.  When it got below freezing these past few weeks, they loaded me in a car and took me to a vet for boarding. This was as much help as my neighbor friends could offer and I will always be grateful to them. It's the first vet care I have ever received. I got some shots, my first bath, and got spayed.  We found out that I am heartworm positive.   Streetdog Foundation was contacted about my situation and came and scooped me and my friend, Ethan, up.  

We are now meeting new human and pup friends, and learning moe about kindness and trust. I'm a little shy at first, but once I love, I love BIG! I was born around 1/25/2013 and on my way to beating these pesky heartworms and officially becoming adoptable. So far I LOVE car rides, and I love booty scratches and hugs. Leashes and stairs are still kinda scary to me but I think I'll end up liking those soon! I have soulful eyes and a big silly grin and can't wait to find out what it is like to live inside a house! So if you can foster me or even better, adopt me, I would love to meet you!

Medical Update: Uma has successfully completed her heartworm treatment.

Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

Meet Babar Bear! Late 2018 Streetdog was informed of a family living on the streets of Memphis. While there were originally 9 puppies plus Mom & Dad it seemed there were only 4 of the  puppies remaining with Mom & Dad. We snatched up the hairless little puppies (#sdfBabyElephants) right away and treated them for heavy mange. Mom & Dad, now #sdfRella & #sdfBabarBear, were much more street savvy and elusive. Took a bit of time but in January 2019, with a little bit of luck, a lot of patience and some Pirtles Chicken,  our vigilant volunteers were finally able to pick the pair up. 

May 18th update: Babar has completed heartworm treatment and has been neutered.

Foster Update: One word…GOOFY! This boy is something else! He’s been used to living on the street is whole life but you would never know it. Fits right in! He is the sweetest of the sweet. Loves to play with other pups and be a part of a pack. His heart is so clearly full of love. The happiest and most goofy pup I’ve ever met! He’s a perfect little nub in his crate.  Sleeps with me and my two dogs, at night,  sans crate perfectly. Truly a beautiful, low-key and amazing boy! He was neutered in  May and has completed heart-worm treatment. Healthy as can be! If we did not have 4 dogs this boy would be mine! Anyone that ends up with this precious boy will be so lucky!

My name is Gracie. Everyone tells me I am beautiful. They say they can tell what the weather will be based on "Gracie having a good hair day"!  I will be five soon and I weigh a trim 85 lbs. I am in the prime of my life and will be make a delightful companion for the right person.  I am looking for the right situation with a foster or adopter who will believe in me and help me overcome my fears. I should be an only dog, though I might get along with a submissive male after proper introductions. A cat companion would be fine. I am also slow to trust so when I first meet you, I might bark at you. You may think I don’t like you but take me for a walk and you will be my new best friend! I love to play with sticks and balls outside. Right now I am not that comfortable around new people but I will be very loving once I get to know you. Trust is an issue for me because of my previous life with people, especially children not being kind to me, so there should be no small children in your home. If you think you might like to be my special person, there are many people supporting me and they would love for you to meet me!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Lynn & Cedric (lynnwelcomesyouhome@gmail.com) for more information about this pet. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!UPDATE - Nick has been diagnosed with Addisons. He will be on meds the rest of his life. Cost is about $250 per month. He feels so great after his monthly shot. You will have to watch him closely as his levels can tank rather quickly.Hi! My name is Nick. I guess you would like to know a little about me and my story. I somehow found myself in a high kill shelter a few months ago. After a few days in the shelter when no one came to get me, they put a slip on my kennel that said I was next to be euthanized if more dogs came into the shelter. Luckily a nice shelter worker contacted 2nd Chance 4 Life and my new foster mom and her friend drove 7 hours each way to come get me! I was so happy to be out of the loud shelter that I slept like a baby the entire way home! As you can tell I am on the older side, but don't let that deter you. I have been told by everyone I meet that I am a sweet old soul. I love curling up into a little ball and sleeping on anything comfy. Did I mention I like to sleep A LOT? I am most happy on a nice warm couch next to my human. I get scared and anxious when I am home alone, and would prefer if someone would stay home with me during the day! Maybe an older soul like me will give me a chance and all the snuggles I could ever want! I like other dogs, and they seem to like me too. I am house trained, I can sit, shake with both paws, and come on command. Please give me a chance to show you that old dogs are just as fun and loving as a young puppy. You wont regret it! - NickPlease fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:

He is an energetic, playful, mature boy who enjoys getting head rubs and giving kisses.  Due to no fault of his own, Gino was surrendered to an overcrowded shelter with his companion Mona (who is also available for adoption through BarkVille Dog Rescue).  Fortunately, BarkVille was able to save them, but Gino needs an IMMEDIATE FOSTER or ADOPTER to get him out of boarding.  He received medical care for his eye and while he is most likely blind in it, it does not seem cause him any discomfort.  However, because of his age and limited sight, we think he may be best suited to a home with no other dogs and mature adults.  He is housebroken, crate trained, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.

For more information about Gino, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt Gino, please submit an adoption application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/adoption-application.

animal.description:
Pumpkin is part of AHAS’s rehabilitation program, which stabilizes and retrains dogs who come to us with behavioral issues. We want the very best for all of the dogs and therefore recommend adopters interested in Pumpkin, participate in the private training workshops we offer to help prepare dog and owner for a smooth transition and happy forever home! 

Meet Pumpkin, a very petite and beautiful female redbone coonhound. This girl is looking for a home that will understand her unique needs. Pumpkin is a sensitive girl and is very scared of storms. She also has separation anxiety.  She takes medicine to help her relax, but she does best when she can have a dedicated safe spot or just be with the person/people she trusts. With time, she has gained confidence in her foster home and is doing much better. We encourage potential adopters to work with us to ensure that we can help her succeed in her forever home.

This girl is currently in a foster home with other dogs and cats. She is respectful around kitties. She has been around small and large dogs and is super playful and occasionally bossy. 

Pumpkin is looking for a home that will give her guidance and leadership so she can feel secure and confident. This girl is ready to go to a home and give kisses 

Pumpkin shines when she has people that help show her the appropriate way to act in situations- when to give kisses (and she LOVES to give kisses to her fav people!) and when to trust a new person. We are happy to work with interested adopters and Pumpkin and share all the many things we adore about this girl! Ask us for more info!

Pumpkin is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and housebroken. We require an adoption application, home visit, and adoption fee. Want more info? Email mastiffmojo@msn.com. Thanks!

Please note, RAGOM's adoption territory includes Minnesota, Iowa, North and South Dakota, and western Wisconsin within 75 miles of the MN border.   At this time, we do not adopt out of our territory.  

Cara is looking for a special family to call her own. This 9-year-old Golden spent her pre-RAGOM years in a commercial breeding facility and had no experience of a normal life, making her extremely shy and wary of any changes.

With guidance and reassurance from her foster pack, Cara is learning to appreciate the good life and taking small steps out of her shell every day. She will need another large, confident dog in her forever home to ensure a successful transition and to facilitate with her training. And to keep her safe and free from stress, we are requiring a home with a physically fenced yard and children in the home must be 10+.

To learn more about Cara see her bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/cara-18-153

Good With Kids: 10+

Age: 9

animal.description:
Rescued:  September 16th, 2018
Age at the time rescue:  3 weeks
Current weight:  40 pounds

*In need of a patient home. This little boy has clearly been with us a long time and it's because he is need of a special home who will give him the time to feel safe loved and develop a routine. We want so desperately for him to have a loving family, but we know that in this busy world, we are asking a lot. We are holding out hope that somewhere there is someone that is the right fit. 

Look at that smile! Wally is one happy boy - rescued with his two siblings, Willy & Waltz, Willy has gone on to find a loving and patient home while Waltz has became part of our sanctuary family because his fear of new people is so strong. That leaves Wally. We believe that Wally is capable of finding a family and we won't give up. He has no aggression whatsoever, but is timid with anything new. Once he learns the ropes, he's good to go which is why we must keep trying. Rescued in 2018 at approximately 3 weeks of age from a Burger King garden area.  His condition was poor, but look at him now.  Wally is shy at first meeting, but warms up with time and routine. He is currently in training learning to trust a bit more quickly.  We are looking for a home where he can feel love and security to blossom. Fully vetted, sterilized and ready to fly home. If you'd like to adopt Wally, please log onto our website at www.scarpr.org and click on How to Adopt.  For any additional questions, please email ronda@scapr.org.  His adoption fee is $400 which includes transportation off the island.  Thank you ~

I get along with medium to large dogs but I chase cats, squirrels, rabbits and small dogs.  I know the sit and come command.  I will come quickly with the rattle of a bag.  Lol!  My foster home gave me a big soft bed but I chose the smaller soft bed because I like to curl up tight when I sleep.  I will require a fenced yard at my new forever home.  I love running and bouncing off leash in a fenced yard with the biggest smile on my face.  I still have some spunk for a senior girl.  If you are looking for a companion who likes to go for walks and snuggle next to you on the sofa while we watch TV then I'm your girl!  Please consider giving me a chance.  You can complete an application at www.safeanimalhaven.org.  Thank you!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Miranda Is A Cancer Survivor Who Needs A Home!!

We rescued Miranda from the Riverside Shelter the day she was to be euthanized. She had mammary tumors on both sides, she had surgery to remove them all and now our sweet girl is sitting in boarding. A cancer survivor deserves better, she deserves a loving home, warm bed and all the walks she wants. Can you give that to her?

Miranda is 8 years young, she is in very good health overall. Her tumors were removed (she has the long s
cars to prove it) and we got all the cancer with good margins. She is fabulous on the leash, loves her walks (she is up to 45 minutes), she knows basic commands, is house trained and loves every person she meets. Miranda would do best as an only dog as she gets stressed sharing a home. We believe it was from the over breeding she was subjected to. She is fine with dogs out on walks, she does pack walks everyday.

Email dogs@labradorsandfriends.org or fill out our online application at
www.labradorsandfriends.org
Miranda is located in Southern California.

In the Beginning: Our sweet senior from the Riverside Shelter has had both her mastectomies and she is now ready to get into a foster or forever home!! Miranda is a LOVE!! She still has zip in her step and loves to go on walks (and hanging out and giving kisses to people!) We want to get Miranda into a home as soon as possible, she deserves it after all she has been through. Miranda would do best in a "only dog" home. She is house trained and great on the leash!

Miranda is a SWEET, 9 year old girl who was in danger of euthanasia at the Riverside Shelter because she is a senior. We pulled her yesterday and took her right to our vet for the senior work up. The good news, her blood work and chest x-rays look good, the bad news, she has 3 mammary tumors that need to be removed. It appears our sweet girl has already had a few removed as she is missing a couple of nipples. We want to get the tumors removed ASAP! We
need to raise $1000 to cover her surgery and biopsy. Please help us help this sweet, sweet girl!!

animal.description:
*PLEASE NOTE:  We do not adopt out on a first-come/first-serve basis.  Applications are accepted for a dog and then a home check is scheduled.  If there are multiple applications for a dog, after all home checks are done,  the dog is adopted out to the home that is the best fit for that dog.
 
 ******Chicagoland Dog Rescue reserves the right to restrict adoption of a dog to potential adopters who live within a fifty (50) mile radius of Schaumburg, IL *****

Hi, my name is Oliver!  I won the foster home lottery with my wonderful foster family but what I really want is to find my forever person or family!  I  still have puppy energy  and I am a strong guy who is working on learning everything I need to be a great dog.  Not to brag but my foster Mom saws I have mastered a beautiful sit!  I really love a good peanut butter kong during my quiet times but I am all about going for a walk outside and playing with a ball.  And I promise that with me around you won’t ever have to worry about squirrels in the yard!!!!  I truly enjoy the company of people and can jump over the gate to keep my foster Mom company while she cooks!  I would love to meet you, so fill out a pre application or email and my foster Mom will get back to just as quick as quick can be!
XOXOXO-Oliver



**The ADOPTION FEE for this pet is $400 which includes getting the puppy/dog up to date on rabies, distemper and bordetella vaccines, fecal test and deworming if necessary, heartworm test, spay or neuter (not including pre-surgical bloodwork) and a microchip. Free access to our weekly training classes is also included for the life of the dog, something no other rescue in the area offers.***

animal.description: What a gorgeous hunk Rusty is! He is a sweet and active 4 year old boy who likes other dogs but can be rough with little dogs ~ he likes to tug and run. He walks well on a leash but you need a strong hand when it comes to meeting other dogs on a walk. He wants to be friendly but he is like a bull in a china shop. He LOVES walks and they are very necessary to tire him out for sleeping at night. Although Rusty gets along with dogs his size, he would be fine as an only dog also - just make sure that he gets plenty of exercise. Rusty MUST be fed separately and not allowed to roam when other dogs in the house are eating. He is gentle taking treats from you but he wants everyone else’s treats or food and that can cause fights. He will try and steal your food also, so best to keep him separated when you are eating. Rusty will need to continue to remain on his prescription food. Rusty is housebroken but NEEDS a consistent schedule. The crate has been very good for him. His new family must understand that he goes out immediately after meals and playtime. Rusty is a good boy but cannot be in a home with children since he plays rough and is HIGHLY food aggressive. He would be fine in a home with teenagers or older who understand and can respect Rusty’s space, with his issues. If you have the perfect home for Rusty, please fill out an Adoption Application.

animal.description:
Lucas is a sheltie mix that came in to the local shelter as a stray. He was found wandering around the lake and had a terrible case of sarcoptic mange. He has been thru treatment for the mange and his hair is starting to grow in and cover the bald places. He is also up to date on all of his vaccinations, heartworm negative, and on heartworm preventative. Lucas is about 14 inches tall and came in to rescue weighing around 14 pounds. Lucas is a happy go lucky puppy that has just gotten into a foster home and we will be learning more about him, his personality and what he knows.

UPDATE: Lucas is over his case of sarcoptic mange and after noticing that the fur was not growing back on his face and feet we took him to a dermatologist. It was determined that Lucas may have what is commonly called collie nose or DM (Dermatomyositis). It is not contagious but a genetic issue that effects a small percentage of shelties and collies. Here is a website with information concerning DM: http://www.illinoissheltierescue.com/dm.html . Lucas is a sweet well behaved sheltie mix. He is house trained and crate trained and has excellent house manners. He loves to go on walks and interacts well with other dogs and with people he meets on those walks. We took him to Barnes and Noble when we were gift wrapping at Christmas and he was a wonderful ambassador meeting and smoozing with all of the visitors. He is currently around 9 years old and is looking for his forever home. He would love an active home as he loves to run and play with toys. He also gets along well with small children and other dogs.

animal.description:
Forest is a super precious pup who just loves to have fun!    He's a 2 year old, 50 pound bundle of love.  He loves  belly rubs and is super-duper friendly!!  He could play all day long chasing a ball or fetching a stick.  He loves other dogs, kids, and pretty much all humans.    Sweet Forest was rescued as an abandoned dog and is so thankful to have humans to take care of him, but what he really wants is his very own family.   This precious boy deserves his very own yard to play in & his very own people.     Won't you be his forever family to love him and let him be your faithful and loyal boy pup?   He will add so much joy to some very lucky family!

Like many rescue pups, this furbaby is HW+, but is currently undergoing the *slow-kill method of treatment (see more information below).  

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies thru date of adoption. This pup is heartworm positive and is currently being treated with the *slow kill method, approved by her veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention. 

*The slow kill method of treatment, simply stated, is a 30 day regiment of  doxycycline followed by a monthly dose of Advantage Multi for 12 months, then retesting.   Most dogs test negative after one year of following this treatment; however, we always recommend that potential adopters consult & follow the advice of their family veterinarian upon adopting any of our hw+ pups.   Although the fast-kill method is still considered the "gold-standard" by the AVA, and may be preferred by some vets; the slow-kill method has proven to be effective in our rescue. The main reason we utilize this method is due to our limited financial constraints and the high number of our rescue pups that are infected.   In the cases of severe infection and if the pup is highly symptomatic, we sometimes use the fast-kill approach instead.   Again, we recommend for you to consult with your veterinarian after the adoption is complete and follow their recommendations.   

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority, but not all, of our pets require a fenced yard or secure enclosure.  In the case of apartments, we require Landlord approval and designated dog area in complex.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport puppies under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees low; however, please keep in mind that the fees we charge do not cover all costs for the pup.  Any additional donations are greatly appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meet & greet for any of our pups.  Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events.   Our events are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails (with landlord appoval).
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs and treated a part of family. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

animal.description:
**Due to the Covid 19 pandemic, our Adoption Team has decided to officially put all adoptions on pause. The health and safety of all involved is of utmost importance. Blind Dog Rescue Alliance prides ourselves in our very careful and thorough screening process of all applicants, and with all the current restrictions in our country, this is just not possible. We would not be able to conduct in-person home visits, a very important part of the process, nor would we be able to provide transport. As applications come in, they will be placed on hold until restrictions are lifted. Once restrictions have been lifted, we will reach out to the potential adopters to see if they are still interested before proceeding. If you have any questions please contact adoption@blinddogrescue.org. We appreciate your understanding during these difficult times.

Blind Dog Rescue Alliance will transport within reasonable distance. Walker is being fostered in NJ.

What we know about Walker:
*is epileptic and on phenobarbital
*young and loves to play
*learning manners
*housebroken
*sweet
*can see some in bright light, but has trouble in dim light

What Walker's foster mom has to say about Walker:
Walker is a solid, young dog. He is respectful of corrections, but loves to play non-stop if he can. He is a growly player. So expect him to talk back. He is learning from his foster home and four-legged family. Walker knows to go into his crate to be fed and he sleeps there too.

Walker has limited vision as he has difficulty seeing in low light.  He has totally detached retinas possibly due to some sort of trauma. He does not appear to be in pain. The vet observed the eye movement (similar to vestibular) and the “off" gait he has. While exaggerated stepping is associated with the blindness, the limited correction of the paws when they fold over, and the wide spread of his body movements may be neurological.  Walker may be a little bit different but it does not slow him down.

Walker will bark and scratch a door when he wants to go out. When crated, he will bark, when loose he goes straight to the door and scratch. He will notify you when it is time to be fed and will run right into his crate and patiently wait for his bowl. He, however, does not like when another dog comes around his food. 
Walker is anxious with new situations such as getting into the car, going to the vet etc. but settles when he has time to work out what is going on.  

 Walker is not comfortable around a lot of dogs and will probably do best in a home as an only dog with owners who are not away for long hours. He’s a doll when cuddling by himself with his person or people. Total devotion. Takes treats ever so nicely (even from the vet techs he just met), needs some leash walking help. Still tries to chew on your shoes while your feet are still in them, loves to have you try and chase him, plays tug-of-war with rope toys, totally loves his Kong with cheese and any Nylabone.
Blind Dog Rescue has voted against the use of electric fencing effective immediately.

Thankfully, a Good Samaritan intervened and was able to save me before I could be seriously harmed.  Because of me not having a ideal start in life, I am very shy and weary of new people but will warm up with time.  I really need that special someone who is willing to work on breaking down my shy shell.  Is that special someone you?  I really need someone to just sit with me and win me over with treats (yum).  I want to trust someone so badly.

If you are not able to adopt me, please consider virtually adopting me or coming to spend time with me on the weekends!

Please visit havenacs.org for our visitation hours, information about the adoption process and to fill out an application!

animal.description:
Fiji is a very sweet, happy, and loyal dog. She likes to lounge around, sit next to you and is always VERY happy to see you. She is also an athletic dog that requires daily exercise, so a fenced in yard is required for Fiji to stretch her legs and play. She absolutely loves her dog toys and would prefer daily walks too!

Currently Fiji is living her best life now, but her young puppyhood was a rough start for her.  Not only was she severely malnourished, but she did not have good experiences with other dogs.  Due to this early trauma, Fiji just prefers to be an only dog.  Other dogs just make her nervous, so she wants a home that respects that and loves her just for the way she is. 

Fiji does do well with children, but due to her muscular size she would do best with older children.

 If you are interested in Fiji, or have more questions about her, please contact her foster mom Tomoko at tdeguchi@yahoo.com, or you can follow Fiji on her foster mom’s Instagram, tdeguchi1201.

**Invisible fence is not a suitable option**

If you would like to meet Fiji then please fill out an application https://www.mynextpet.com/dog-application

animal.description:
Please read the disclaimer before your submit an application.

Meet Buddy! He is about 3 years old and weighs 11 pounds. Buddy is a great little guy for the right adult-only home. He is friendly and happy, but also a little bossy. Once in a home Buddy can get territorial and therefore he will need an experienced owner who understands when he wants to be left alone. He doesn't growl but does some body posturing that will let you know he is uncomfortable. Buddy loves to cuddle and be near you if it's on his terms. He is house trained and is in a foster home with other small dogs.  However, he does not get along with all dogs so it's best if the other dog in the home is submissive, or he is the only dog. Buddy LOVES toys, enjoys short walks and exploring the outside. He will be a wonderful companion for the right owner.

If you are interested in meeting Buddy please first fill out the online adoption application at www.greatpets.org. If you have questions you can email us at info@greatpets.org. Buddy's $250 adoption fee includes his vet exam. vaccinations, neuter surgery, microchip and flea treatment.

*Disclaimer: Buddy is territorial and may bite if he feels cornered or dominated. He has been adopted and returned for behavior. That is why we listed him as special needs. He will require a home committed to ongoing training & management. We are only accepting applications from families with no children under age of 18. *

Sandra Dee’s Story
 My mate (Dany Zuko) and I have been on the streets for 3 1/2 years until we found ourselves stuck in a pit that houses oil. Time passed, and we grew thirsty and drank a lot of the fluid to stay alive. 

After over 3 days we heard sweet voices and they were there to rescue us! They took us to a building called Grace Animal Hospital and more sweet voices welcomed us with open arms. 

We were still terrified of everything, but after a long session of bathing...they got most of the oil off of us and gave us meds for our sickness. They gave us each a warm bed, clean water and good food. We are now resting and getting well. 

We are realizing what love is all about. And we are not so afraid of what happens next anymore. We are now Streetdogs. Not street dogs. But real official Streetdog Foundation Streetdogs. From here on out we will always be safe and loved. We cannot wait to find out what our life will be like from now on!

Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

animal.description:
Last Weigh-in: 78.4 lbs

Update on our newbies from Founder, Melanie Pafford: Danny and sandy are still learning about human love. They had little to no human interaction for their 3 1/2 years. They are taking Burgies gently from us. Slowly but surely is how this is going! Coming to Grace Animal Hospital with hot Burgies is definitely the way to win friends here. Sitting and reading to them. Leaving a t-shirt you slept in with them. It will be a while before they can be leash walked. They are so hesitant about everything right now. But time and love will make all of the difference!

------------------------------------------------------
Danny Zuko’s Story
My mate and I have been on the streets for 3 1/2 years. No one knows if we were ever around with people before... but we have seen people, and have tried to try to find food where they were. We have had to scavenge for what little was available to us for so so long, and just wanted to get somewhere dry and safe. We found an old Quonset hut that was very dark and seemed safe for the moment...until we got spooked, ran, and fell into a deep pit. The bottom of the pit was wet and rock hard when we hit, and we stayed so scared and very sore. We didn’t know what happened, but we knew we were in a very bad place. 

We tried and tried and tried to find a way out of this terrifying hole, but there was no way out for us. It was just too deep. We didn’t know how we were going to survive. Our panic was so high and we were frantic with the fear of how we could live! After crawling around and pacing and searching for just one toehold...one ledge....we settled into the knowledge that we were trapped here. Time passed, and we grew thirsty and hungry. There was nothing down there but the wet chemical smell of machine sludge. We waited. All we could do was hope. We could not tell the passing of days or nights...but our exhausted bodies grew weaker and our hope grew dim. We had to have something inside us or we would die. So we started licking the wet vile tasting dampness from the floor. It made us sick...but it was all we had. 

We knew that there was little hope, but we were trying so hard not to give in to our desperate situation. We had survived on our own for this long...surely this dark hole was not to be our end? But it seemed that was the case. Starved, dehydrated and so sick from what we ingested...we were barely able to lift our heads now. We curled around each other and sadly awaited our fate. In a hazy blur...we heard the sound of a door opening ...footsteps..and voices. A faint pin light was shining back and forth sometimes passing over our dungeon. Finally the voices and light came closer. So close that the light blinded us. We both closed our eyes and pressed together as tight as we could. The voices were frantic for a minute and we stayed still...and then the steps and light faded away and the door closed. When we heard no more sounds for a while we realized that our chances were gone. 

We got up and tried to feel our way around and see if anything had changed...if we could get out.... but no. Same prison. So discouraged, we lay back down and stayed wrapped around each other. We hoped that we wouldn’t have to suffer long. Life is hard for a pup without a home...and we were resigned and sad...but we had no choice. We lay down for what we thought was our last time. Later....through a haze of sickness..we heard the door open again and saw another sweeping of light. What would happen this time? We were too weak to do anything to protect ourselves. We just stayed wrapped together. Maybe the strange noise and light would just go away again and leave us in peace. We couldn’t take any more pain. Suddenly a blast of white light filled a corner of our pit. The voices were back and this time I heard some of them speak softly and sweetly. They were telling us that everything would be okay and to trust us. One of the original voices was saying how he thought there was only one dog because of how close we were pressed to each other. Was this group of voices and shadows coming to help us or harm us? We just didn’t know. A kind man crawled down a metal contraption to where we were and just spoke to us for a while. Another voice sang softly to us. They sounded so gentle. But we had only been chased by humans and kept to ourselves much of our lives. 

We didn’t know what to do. It didn’t matter. We were too weak to do anything. The kind man gently put a soft towel around me and my partner and lifted us each up over his head and to his own partner. She took us in her arms and told us that we were safe and that we would no longer be hungry or thirsty or cold and hopeless anymore. These words sounded so sweet to us! We had never heard such a promise of love...but we were ready to find out what that meant! 

They took us to a building called Grace Animal Hospital, and more sweet voices welcomed us with open arms. We were so so tired but so glad that we were out of that awful dark place. We were still terrified of everything, but after a long session of bathing...they got most of the oil off of us and gave us meds for our sickness. They gave us each a warm bed, clean water, and good food. We are now resting and getting well. Our starvation is still evident, and the nice people are giving many meals a day to help with that. The people who got us out of the pit come every day and talk with us and sing to us, and have started to stroke our fur. This is something we haven’t had done before. So it is kind of scary… but also feels really good. Each of us has a really soft and safe friend whom they call Orange Puppy. We each agree that though he doesn’t talk, he will listen to our worries and let us lay our heads on his shoulders. We trust him most of all right now. We are learning to trust the people with the sweet voices too. We are realizing what love is all about. And we are not so afraid of what happens next anymore. 

We are now Streetdogs. Not street dogs. But real official Streetdog Foundation Streetdogs. From here on out we will always be safe and loved. We cannot wait to find out what our life will be like from now on!  

*Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

Foster Update:  Elena has not been tested with cats or kids yet but I have no doubt she will do great. She’s the sweetest girl I’ve ever had the pleasure of fostering. Very smart! Very gentle and lady-like. She is still shy meeting new people and being in new places but really opens up in no time. Loves playing with toys. She is leash trained. Elena would love a foster or forever home that is sensitive to pups that have lived on the streets and still getting used to the lux life. I have a cap on how many dogs I’m allowed in my city otherwise I’d never let this sweet girl go! 


-----------------------------------------


Elena’s Story
On Tuesday, 1/19/2019, we introduced you to our #sdfJusticePups, Ruth Bader, Ginsburg, and O’Connor. Shortly after we were so happy to finally locate their brother, Kennedy all with the help of some very dedicated volunteers, 

A few hours later, the Memphis Animal Services team was able to get mom (Elena)  and get her transferred over to us! Huge shout out to the Field Officer who was able to scoop her up and to Dani and Alexis for reaching out immediately to let us know we could come to get our mama!  #sdfElena is barely older than a puppy herself but she is so sweet and lets our volunteers carry her into Grace to get checked out.

Elena did test positive for Heartworms but Grace Animal Hospital is getting rid of those nasty buggers. She’s up to date on her vaccinations and is preparing to meet the family of her dreams. Could it be you?

Medical Update: Elena has been spayed and also has successfully completed her heartworm treatment.

Follow us on Facebook for updated photos and more information on our adoptable pets!

Barney is approximately a 2 year old heeler mix. He is a VERY shy guy but with TIME(maybe even months) and PATIENCE he warms up nicely. He is fully potty trained and crate trained. He does good  with other easy going dogs that will give him his space and with proper introductions and doesn't mind cats.  He can be leery of men but again with time and patience he warms up. This is a boy who you can't expect to be your best friend in a week. Barney will need you to give him space and time to warm up to his surroundings.Barney would do best in a home without young children. Barney is looking for his happily ever after. Barney's forever home does require a fenced in yard. 

Barney is vaccinated for rabies, distemper, and bordatella. He is neutered and is microchipped. Barney's adoption fee is $350 plus WI state tax!

If you are interested in meeting Barney, please fill out an application at luckypawsmidwest.org. Once your application is approved, we can set up a time for you to meet him!

animal.description:
Mosby here, reporting for duty!

Mosby is a four-year-old shepherd/aussie/cattle dog mix and weighs around 50 pounds. He's a super smart, very trainable pooch. He already knows a ton of commands, including sit, stay, down, bring it, drop it, leave it, let’s go, come, look, quiet, off, stay back, out, and even can ring a bell to let you know when he needs to go outside.

Some of Mosby's favorite things in the world are: chew toys (especially with squeakers and stuffing to tear out), fetch, soccer (especially if the ball is one he can pick up with his teeth), walks/runs, treats, sleeping on the couch, sitting on the porch, dens (his crate, under the bed), hoarding toys, chasing/be chased by my foster (dog) brother, playful dogs, jumping up to hug you (but only briefly), sleeping on the bed, stretching out on the top of the couch like a cat, looking out the windows, laying upside down, and chasing the red laser dot.

Because he's so darned smart, we think Mosby would do great in a home where he can be a working dog, or in a home with a skilled owner or someone committed to his ongoing training, which The Pet Connection is happy to provide. Do you have a farm or acreage? Need some help from a super savvy pooch? Mosby might be just the helper dog you need! Do you have a quiet, adult-only home and think you might want a smarty- pants dog to train? Mosby could be your boy! Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more information or to set up a time to meet Mosby!

*Check out the cute Mosby baby pics, too!

**Mosby is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and ready to go home! He is in the Kansas City metro area and eligible for a no-cost adoption for an encouraged donation.

#thepetconnection #adoptdontshop #savealife #adoptadog #mosbyneedsyou

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Marika at marikac@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Toby the Terrier
Estimated Breed : Terrier Mix
Approximate Age: 4 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 45 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Toby is a bundle of fun! He is an outgoing fella and loves to play. Once he knows and trusts you, he loves you and wants to be with you as much as possible, he's a great snuggler. Toby is looking for an active family and wouldn't thrive in apartment or urban environment unless you are a very active runner/hiker. Toby loves to play. When we dropped him off with his foster he was so excited to be in the yard! He ran and ran with a big smile on his face. He may be 4yrs old but still has a lot of puppy in him, would be a great jogging companion. Toby is currently with our trainer and has done great on acquiring good doggie manners and obedience training. He also does really well getting along and playing with the 3 doggies in trainer's home. He would do well in a home with a canine buddy or gal who can match his style of play and is playful and energetic like him. Toby is good with children and friendly. Just like any terrier he is a little too interested in kitties so we would not recommend him for a home with one. Toby has been a good boy, acquiring some excellent training and is ready for his forever home. Our trainer will even help you transition Toby into his new home successfully!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Roo was picked up from terrible conditions--she was heart worm positive, mal-nourished,  full of fleas, and her caretaker had passed.  Roo is now a healthy 65 pound, 9 year old black lab mix. She has gained weight and all her fur has grown back into a shiny coat. She is fully housebroken and is pretty good on a leash (she pulled a bit at first, but responds well to correction). She is very sweet and gets along well with my lab.  There are no children in my house, but she has spent time with friends' and family's kids and is very gentle with them. She loves her walks, but also loves exploring the back yard.  She has great energy on her walks, but is mostly chill the rest of the time. She is a sweet angel and would love a loving home! Come and meet Roo at Kristin's in Ft Lauderdale


If you are interested in adopting please go to LRRoF.org NOW and fill out an application.

Thanks so much for your interest in our rescue!
Your support, both through adoption and donation is always essential to us and our Labs. Donate today!
We're about matching the right dog with the right family. All applicants will be assigned an Adoption Counselor who will act as their liaison. In addition, a phone interview, home inspection and vet reference (if applicable) are required for eligibility to adopt from Labrador Retriever Rescue of Florida.
