animal.description:
Axel von Apolda is a very handsome 1-2 year old Shepherd mix.  Axel started his journey to Westside not knowing what life was really about. He previously lived in a rural area where we suspect he was not exposed to many people or different situations. Our professional trainer is working with this special boy who needs an equally special owner -- one who is experienced with dogs, as well as calm and matter-of-fact versus sentimental or overly-affectionate -- one who will continue Axel's transformation, together with some complementary training that Westside will provide in his new adults-only home. Axel has come so far.  He now starts his day calmly and happily when he leaves his kennel.  His leash manners, with just a little reminder, are great and he takes in all the smells of his new life as he walks down the street.  Axel enjoys playgroups and interacts with all the dogs.  He gravitates to the calmer dogs who match his personality and even enjoys playing with them.  Those over-the-top ones, he avoids.  At our rescue facility Axel has become an affectionate boy with the staff.  He needs a little time to become comfortable with new people, so he needs someone willing to be patient with his progress.  Axel will be so grateful for a confident owner whom he can trust to expose him to new experiences in life. 
weighs approx 50-55#

Westside dog Biographies, availability and new photos are updated regularly on our website! So, check in and log on often! 

Westside thanks you for looking at our amazing dogs and for choosing to save an animal's life through rescue. 

Don't forget to visit your local animal shelter...the source of many of our dogs.
 

www.sheprescue.org

https://www.facebook.com/WGSRescue

animal.description:
Maggie, or Moo Moo as affectionately called in her foster home, is quite the love bug and easily motivated by food and treats. Maggie shows and gives affection freely with people she loves and is comfortable with. You can easily find yourself with a Maggie-sized shadow who gives you kisses and hugs anytime you need them. She's an excellent hugger! Maggie can be slow to warm up to men but hasnt had issues with women and older children. 

Maggie is a 4yo Kelpie mix, who true to her breed loves to herd people and other animals. She displays typical herding breed behaviors like nipping at heels, herding other dogs and keeping them in line. She can and has lived successfully with other dogs, however, Maggie needs slow introductions, quick corrections, and a dog who can be submissive to her dominant personality. Her behavior with other dogs will need to be managed on a consistent basis so it experienced dog or herding breed owners are preferred. She will do best with an alpha handler who lets her know that they are the ones in charge, not her. 

Maggie has been attending weekly training classes to work on her leash behaviors and reactivity. Inside the home, Maggie loves sleeping and naps, enjoys a daily walk or active playtime throwing the toys, is crate trained, and potty trained. She loves riding in the car and can be the perfect companion if you want to be a marathon runner one day and a couch potato the next day 

If Maggie might be the right fit for you, please submit an adoption application now! Please apply here: http://www.2babrescue.org/online-application

*HOME OWNERSHIP REQUIRED!*

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet our precious little Lulu girl! Lulu was born in May 2018 and comes into rescue from Texas. This poor girl has already endured so much suffering and neglect in her young life. Lulu has something wrong with her heart and had a very bad case of demodex (non-contagious) mange causing hair loss and her skin to be very raw and infected. Lulu's skin is all fixed up now and we are managing the several congenital heart defects that we discovered she has. She is taking medications to help her heart and had a surgery to prolong her life. Despite our best efforts this sweet girl still has a guarded prognosis. She needs someone very special who can fill the rest of her time here with boundless amounts of love and happiness. Lulu is an absolutely adorable little angel. All it takes is one look into those beautiful eyes and you can see the love and sweetness that she is made of. Her special someone will need to be on board with taking her for frequent check ups to make sure that she continues to thrive for as long as possible but this shouldn't be a big deal because this miracle girl is totally worth it! She is strong willed with a heart of gold and is great with people of all ages (no young children as she's strong and energetic), other dogs and even cats! She is the total package and we can't wait to see her spoiled in her forever home! If you would like to be the lucky one that gets to give Lulu the happy ever after that she is so very deserving of, please fill out an adoption application for her here! Http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

animal.description:
***Available for adoption to experienced dog owners of working/difficult dog breeds (I.e German Shepherd Husky, Akita, Heeler, etc) ***

Name: Harper
Age: Approx. 5 Years as of April 2019
Breed: German Shepherd Dog possible Belgian Malinois mix
Good with Kids: No
Good with Dogs: No
Good with Cats: No

Harper is a beautiful girl that is a credit to her lineage in terms of looks and personality. She has a drive to do a good job. Harper listens attentively, and works to follow commands the best she knows how. We really think that she would do well under any sort of training her new family would care to put her through.

 Harper is the kind of girl that would excel as a working dog with a job. Harper's ideal family would involve no kids, but instead a couple or a single person looking for companionship and looking to have a lifelong friend that they could devote their attention and patience towards.Harper is does well in her crate and great on a leash. She likes to have a job to do, and takes her job of patrolling the grounds seriously. She has taken it upon herself to be the guardian of our staff, and she loves her people very much. 

Harper isn't much for toys, but instead prefers to be on guard and working. She loves chicken! She is great at catching treats and rarely misses. She is very careful with her food not to alarm the person offering it to her. She is quite gentle with people that she knows are the alpha. Harper is currently 75 pounds. Harper is very intelligent and quite serious.Harper may require multiple meet and greets to get an accurate gauge of her personality.

---

http://www.deafdogrescueofamerica.org/adoption-application.html

Please note that we are unable to respond to inquiries, emails or phone calls. Our adoption process starts with completion/submission of an application for adoption. All applications are reviewed as quickly as we can, and our adoption process is not first come, first served. We select our adoptive homes according to what our dogs/puppies require. animal.description:
Hi I am Tyson.  I am 2 years old.  I am tall and lanky with a lot of energy.  I am a graduate of the New Leash on Life program so I know basic commands.   I love to please my people but I'm still learning, so don’t be frustrated with me if you have to repeat things.  I walk great on a leash if I am on your left side.  Completely house trained and will have to have a fenced in yard because I sometimes lose my brain when my nose takes over.    I went in my previous home and it was the greatest thing ever.  I am crate trained, but prefer to sleep with my people.  But the best part is I am such a good boy that I can be trusted out of a crate when no one is home.  Give me a bone and I will be fine.  I don’t realize how big I am, and my tail always wags so fragile things might need to moved to 'higher ground'.   I love, love, love respectful, kind children.  I will be gentle playing with them I promise.
    So you know---deep voiced men scare me,  A LOT.    I am kinda shy to begin with and deep voices really terrify me.     When I get stressed I vomit and get diarrhea.   The reason I am up for adoption is I was just terrified of the man in the house, which broke my heart and their hearts as well.  I need to be the only  dog (and  NO cats!)
  Otherwise everyone says I am the bestest boy ever and will try very hard to make you happy.

foster- Lori M.                                                posted--MR

animal.description:
In 'A Midsummer Night's Dream', Shakespeare writes of Hermia: "And though she be but little, she is fierce". We could not think of a more apt quote to describe our quite small but mighty friend Raven! Raven may be short in stature but she has an infectious personality and spirit that endears her to everyone at our shelter. She has many quirks, such as she gets a little "foamy" around the mouth when playing with a favorite toy, but it's all of her quirks that make Raven into such a fascinating dog. 

Raven came to us from our rescue partner that helps transport dogs from Miami to the Northeast and from day one we knew we had a special dog on our hands. It was not just Raven's looks, but also physically how she walked and moved. Raven has myotonia congenita which may make her movements slower than your typical dog but does not stop her from enjoying dog playdates and stretching out for scratches like a cat. She is an incredibly special soul that lights up whenever she is around her friends (both human and stuffed toys) and is waiting for her very own family to come along and see just how incredible she really is!



Contact the Adoptions team at (914) 273-1674 or adoptions@adoptadog,org for more information!

The first step to adopting one of our dogs is to fill out our online adoptions questionnaire located here: https://forms.gle/5heEH8S6c7zXBneD7

animal.description:
This sweet girl is Shelby.  She is a 2 year old, 46 lb pocket pit bull mix.  Shelby was found on the side of the highway where she was dumped with her food bowl.  Lucky for her, one of the members of our rescue noticed the dog bowl on the side of the road so she pulled over and out came Shelby to greet her.  She came out tail wagging with lots of kisses so happy to see someone.  She had a couple cuts on her head but she is all fixed up now and ready for her forever home.   

Shelby loves loves loves people.  She just wants to give everyone she meets a big kiss.  She is so happy to meet anyone and greets you with a full body wag.  Shelby does fine passing dogs and does great playing with them through a fence but she is not good with dogs once they are in her space so she is going to have to be an only dog in her home.  She is really great and friendly with people so she'd be good with older kids however since we haven't had her around small children we aren't sure how she'd be. 

Shelby would like a home where she has a fenced yard to run and play in.  She'd love a home where she got to go on walks and get lots of love, toys, and snuggle time.  

Shelby is currently in boarding so we are not sure if she is house trained however she does keep her kennel clean.  

Shelby is spayed, microchipped, and current on her vaccines.  Her adoption fee is $175.  

If you would like to adopt Shelby and make her a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

NOTE: ELIANNA NEEDS A FENCED YARD AND SHE DOES NOT LIKE OTHER DOGS SO SHE MUST BE THE ONLY DOG.IN THE HOME.

ELIANNA is an energetic and playful, 3-year-old, 55-pound Plott Hound mix. FROM ELIANNA'S FOSTER GUARDIAN "Elianna (Elle or Ellie for short) is a happy, affectionate, smart & sweet girl. She has a positive presence that keeps you smiling. Elle is very well adjusted, She settles into new environments fast. She listens & learns quickly. Elle is a true companion, she lives to be by your side. Elle is always ready to cuddle & she loves to rest her head on you. She just wants to be near you, will follow you around, so pleased to be part of your life. Elle enjoys activities & car rides but also loves to relax and snuggle on the couch. She is generally a calm dog, has spurts of energy then tires out. A fenced yard is best so she can do her silly sprints & sunbathe in nice weather. " *** ELIANNA is a fun-loving young dog, friendly and good-natured. She would be a perfect fit for a person or family who would appreciate the friendship of a dog who's game for anything! She'd be an outstanding camping or hiking companion and would enjoy doing things like going to the park, playing frisbee, fetching a ball, jogging or walking around the neighborhood, being your co-pilot on road trips or just taking evening coffee rides. She's also an affectionate and cuddly little mush, and would be happy to keep you cozy and warm on the couch while you binge-watch your favorite Netflix series together! ELIANNA is a fantastic dog, who'll be an excellent friend and companion to the lucky person or family who adopts her! WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Levi is about 11 years young, is grey and white in color, and is a sweet older gentleman. He is a typical IG - a “Velcro” dog that loves nothing more than to be on his humans lap. He can get a little possessive of “his” lap, however, his foster family has been working with Levi and he is getting better with sharing his people.

Levi is very good about pottying outside but is also pad trained.  He does well in a crate when his foster family isn’t home, and sometimes enjoys laying in there when the door is open when they are home.  If you are looking for a dog that will snuggle on your lap and be your companion, you have found your match!

Levi also came into rescue with his “brother” Bailey, who is about 12 years young. He’s a complete gentleman who enjoys the company of humans and other dogs alike.

Like Levi, Bailey has zero potty issues - pottying outside isn’t a problem for him and he is also pad trained if kept in a dog-safe room or crated for a few hours, as he also likes his crate and having some quiet time on occasion. Bailey isn’t a lap dog per se, but he loves being scratched and pet and sharing your company.

Bailey has some facial paralysis due to an unknown cause from his younger years but experiences no other related symptoms.  Because of this his right eye waters a bit and his right ear sticks straight up which gives him cutest character!

Levi and Bailey are both neutetered, are up to date on all of their vaccines and vetting needs, are both on a kidney diet wet food, and both take inexpensive medications daily.

We would love to see them adopted together as they are best buds and have been through a lot together. If you’re interested in adopting Levi and Bailey please visit our website at www.IgRescueOhio.org and submit an adoption application so we can start the process for you.
animal.name: Levi and Bailey

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: American Staffordshire Terrier, American Bulldog, Chow Chow Gender: Female Estimated Date of Birth: December 17, 2016 Size: 50 lbs Location: Woodstock, GA
RESCUING WINNIE
Our friends at Fulton County Animal Services contacted us on behalf of Winnie, formerly known as Steph, with a desperate plea for help. Winnie came in as a stray, dragging a leash, in terrible shape, with an awful upper respiratory infection. She was lethargic, not eating, had diarrhea, was vomiting, and had nasal discharge. Her body temperature was 105 degrees, when a normal dog temp is about 101 to 102. She crashed quickly and they brought her to the Emergency clinic, however the shelter is no place for a dog in such critical condition. Lucky for Winnie, we had a foster step up to see her through her recovery. Winnie had a terrible case of pneumonia and her lungs sounded very wet, but after many weeks of breathing treatments and antibiotics, her lungs finally cleared.
ABOUT WINNIE
Winnie was a trooper through her medical treatments and has proved to be a wonderful lady. She has also done well with and enjoys the company of the other dogs in her foster home. Winnie is a happy go lucky gal that enjoys exploring outside and going for car rides. She gets very excited about going to rides and is a super strong gal. Her foster family is working with her on not pulling on the lead. At her foster home, you will likely find her chewing her Benebones or simply following her people around the house. She is a fairly active dog who will do best with regular exercise, or maybe even a doggie sibling to zoom around the yard with. She is crate-trained, housebroken, fully vetted, and ready for a forever family!
Winnie's DNA test results are back and she is 75% American Staffordshire Terrier, 12.5% American Bulldog, and 12.5% Chow Chow
Photo Album of Winnie: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2444899182234900
Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Shooter is in search of a new home through no fault of his own.  His owner died and the man's wife did not want to keep him.  He was born in November 2018, and was raised as an inside dog.  He was then given to his most recent owner who kept him as an outside dog.  When that person died, his relatives were unwilling to take Shooter back.  Shooter is food aggressive, with humans and other animals, and needs someone willing to work with him. Shooter rides well in a car.  He is  very smart and quick to learn.   He is a talker and makes all kind of noises to communicate with you, which is unusual for a Great Pyr.  Shooter would do best with someone familiar with the breed. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 10 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Shooter will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

NOTE: Please read our entire write-up before contacting us. If you don't know the age, breed, weight, what vet care we provide our dogs, the adoption fee, or how to apply, you have not read the write-up. 

Kellis

Breed: Chihuahua
Gender: Male, neutered
DOB:   3-19-2015
Weight:    6 pounds
Microchipped  
Adoption Fee:  $250

Kellis had an odd start. We don't know if his owner had him his entire life or got him as an adult. What we do know is that his owner had not worked on poor behavior and had not properly socialized Kellis. He was a barking, snapping, snarling, growling, howling mess when he entered our program!

Today, Kellis enjoys people, enjoys lap time, loves going for walks and has liked just about every new person he has met. He still has people that scare him and he will bark at them. Simply correct him, choose if you want to work on the issue then- or just move on. He's a fun and loving dog and, in the right hands, should continue to be a great little companion!

Good w/ Other Dogs- Yes
Good w/ Cats- Unknown, but may be fine
Energy Level- Moderate
Children- No. While he did well with kids in his last home, we will not chance it
Grooming Needs- Low
Walks on Leash- Yes
Special Needs- No
Knows basic commands- No 
Experienced Home- Required
Good First Time Dog- No
Rides well in car-  Yes
Crate Trained-  Yes
Low Allergen- No
Good apartment dog- No    

Adoptive homes within the  Raleigh, NC area only.

If you are interested in adopting this pet, please copy and paste this link to our adoption survey into your browser:  https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdehkuFyLcCDhVB4SWB0h3aNCHUCHA8lZemxr3dUYl2wM8zyg/viewform?c=0&w=1! 

This dog attends Cary Meet and Greet events!  Not all pets in our program attend every event.  We do not arrange meetings with our pets, outside Meet and Greet events, without an approved application.

All HEART dogs have been spayed/neutered, vaccinated for rabies, distemper, parvo, adenovirus, and hepatitis. Some have been vaccinated for Bordatella. All are tested for heartworms and, if they test positive, have either been treated or provided alternative slow-kill treatment. Dogs are provided monthly heartworm and flea prevention. Dogs are also provided additional medical care, as needed. This care may include amputations, wound repair, treatment for skin disorders, dental care, treatment for infection and other medical needs.

animal.description:
ADOPTION FEE:$100

Owen is a boxer/pit bull mix who was found as a stray, and is about 10 yrs old and 75 lbs.  He must have lived in a home before, as he has been wonderfully behaved in his foster home, without any accidents, chewing or getting into things. When left alone, he will hang out on the couch and wait.  He is friendly with people, loves going for walks, playing with balls, taking the stuffing out of stuffed squeaky toys, curling up with his fleece blanket, laying in the sun, chasing squirrels and bees, and running around the yard.  

He walks well on a leash, though can pull strongly if he sees a something to chase.  After his walk, he doesn’t mind spending the morning sleeping or relaxing and looking out the window. He has a good amount of energy and gets quite active and playful in the later in the day.  He does well with 2 walks a day and yard time to play and run.   He can get boisterous when he plays so a home without small children would be best.

Owen would do best as an only dog, but possibly with a friendly small dog or cat.  He doesn’t live with other pets in his foster home, and seems to like meeting the small dogs, but is not as receptive to larger ones.  There's not much interest in playing or sharing his toys with other dogs once he’s met them. He passed a cat test at the shelter though shows interest in chasing strays. 

Owen's back knees are stiff from arthritis, with limited range of motion, and he is careful of them when laying down, and will sit or lay with his legs sticking out. It doesn’t stop him from jumping and running around or climbing a few stairs, and he does well with a soft place to lay where he can stretch out and rest when needed.  He likes to sit in the car, but doesn’t do so well on rides.  Owen doesn't tolerate being crated, and will need a fenced yard.

animal.description:
Zhoey came to us from an owner who had no idea how to help her. When she went to her foster home, the skin on her belly was like leather. Her issue was allergies. They caused itching so bad that she was missing fur. She had never been socialized with other dogs, but she quickly learned that her four-legged foster brothers could protect her and teach her. They taught her that the vacuum wasn’t so scary and that the dogs she encountered on her walks weren’t all so bad.

Zhoey has come a long way too with her allergies. She is on a special diet and taking medication, but now her fur is the softest and shiniest, with no more bald patches. She is a beauty. She gets regular baths and never gives her foster a hard time. She loves to prance around after every bath letting her foster brothers know she smells oh so much better than they do. Maybe they can be next.

Did we say that Zhoey’s come a long way? Oh, yes. Her buddies taught her that it was okay to be in the big world and that it is fun to play, and that is what she loves to do. Zhoey is a super high-energy dog that loves to run and play with her dog friends. She can do laps through the gardens, around the fruit trees, as fast as the fastest. She can wear the fastest out, but when they’re done, she will happily move on to her next friend. She also loves and very much respects her 11-year-old “mama dog” and mentor. She loves to follow her around, probably learning new things with every step of the way.

Like some dogs who have gone through their own issues, Zhoey is very empathic to those around her. She looks into your eyes with those beautiful sweet brown eyes like she knows that you are in pain and would gladly lay her head down on your knee just to be able to could help you like she was helped before. Zhoey is a special girl who can make you laugh when you need it, give you a wet sloppy kiss when you need it, and just be by your side when you need it.

If Zhoey could make her dream list for her future home, it would, of course, include a family that will take care of her forever, but also she would love some four-legged canine friends to play with. After all, not many humans can keep up with her puppy energy. She would love a big yard to run and play with her friends in too, and if there are lizards and squirrels, oh, that would be so much fun. She’ll make sure she keeps your garden safe from them.
Please visit http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/ to learn more about our dogs. Click on available dogs to see further descriptions. If you are interested in me, please contact us at information@coastalgsrsd.org or call (858) 779-9149. Don't forget to fill out our online application:  http://www.coastalgsrsd.org/webform/1774/adoption-application.

The minimum adoption donation ranges from $300 to $400. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100% tax deductible.

Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.All of the animals posted on our site have been temperament tested. While not all are in the immediate area, once we have processed and approved your application, we will move the dog to our adoptive area for you to meet, greet and hopefully adopt. Sometimes we will have more than one application on a dog. That does not mean it automatically goes to another family but you should be aware of the fact that until you are approved and set up for the meet/greet.. the dog could get adopted by another applicant.Heath is a young dog and ready to be an ideal best friend and family dog. He has a naturally sweet and happy temperament. He wants to hear you say 'Good boy' a lot, so he will listen to what you want and then try his best to do it. He is full of life and friendliness and is going to love playing in your backyard and going for walks. Even better, he would be delighted to accompany you for jogs or hikes, or camping. He is good with most other dogs, however, he is very strong and likes to play a little rough. We have made sure he is all ready to go by getting him all his shots and a thorough vetting. He is ready to begin life with you and to show you what a good dog he is. A SPECIAL NOTE TO YOU FROM HIS FOSTER: Heath is a young healthy, housetrained dog who loves people, loves kids but may be too strong for younger children. He is a bit too interested in cats so probably better not to have any in his new home. He is crate trained, takes treats gently, and is smart as a whip. All ready knows sit, and paw and is working on come. Heath is a high energy dog and will need someone that can exercise him multiple times a day to keep him happy. He's just an overall good dog. Heath loves to play so a fenced yard is needed so he can run off all that energy! No cats and most likely only dog because of his energy.
Heath needs a very active family as he likes exercise!
If you are interested in Heath, please contact:
rorrcanine@gmail.com

animal.description:
Have you seen a prettier pooch? We think not! Star is our friend from Saving Deathrow Dogs. She is a six-year-old lab mix and on the larger size at about 149 pounds.

Star was adopted from a shelter as a puppy and returned six years later. The poor girl was itchy, had hair loss and horribly infected ears, and was urinating blood when she came to The Sanctuary by the Pet Connection. Her untreated chronic allergies were causing her major discomfort. She was in pain and so frightened that we couldn't touch her for eight weeks. ? Now that she's had proper medical care, good food, and a loving, supportive environment, Star is feeling sooooo much better! ??

Star is a fantastic dog. Some might even call her . . . a Star! ?? She is housebroken and not at all destructive. She's good on leash and very obedient. Star is also a fan of good movies, particularly when viewed with her human on the couch, perhaps with a belly rub! ?? But Star does have another side -- she is a silly goofball, too! ?

Star likes most other dogs but would prefer that they not mess with her food and toys. ?? (Gottta admit, we're with her on that one! ?) She's still a shy girl but does great with a slow introduction to new people. After what she's been through, who could blame her for wanting to carefully assess her new peeps? ?

The Pet Connection will happily provide her foster and forever homes with behavioral support for Star, including proper introductions to strangers entering the home. Her medical needs aren't complicated -- treatment for her ears and skin and daily medication. ?

Can you help Star put her best paw forward? ? Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more info on fostering or adopting this Star!

*Star is staying with The Pet Connection in Beloit, KS, but transport is available for the right home!

animal.description:
We rescued Beauty a while back .. she has some costly skin issues and has suffered abuse so is unpredictable in her temperament.  She takes 3 types of prescription drugs plus monthly flea and tick meds, and grain free food, to help keep her allergies and skin issues in check. Because she is so very reactive and skiddish, she is not a good candidate for adoption.  She lives in foster care with several other dogs but does continue to be overly reactive with everyone, 2 legged and 4.

All of Beauty's meds, vet care and special food are costly.  If you would like to help by sponsoring or just donating for Beauty's care, please donate via paypal to dalrescue@sbcglobal.net.  There is a donate button for paypal on the website, dalrescuesocal.com or you can go thru paypal.com.  Beauty is doing well in foster care and is finally beginning to understand that humans and other dogs can be her friends. We are very glad we are able to keep her comfortable and happy in foster care.  If you can help please do email us at dalrescue@sbcglobal.net.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on our facebook page at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing your photos and photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  thanks!

animal.description:
Liv loves relaxing more than anything else on earth.  She is a sweet girl who has had a tough past. She has come a long way in the 2 years she has been in our rescue. Liv is a tripod (3 legs) but gets around like a normal dog. 

Liv has recently lost some much needed pounds. It’s hard to say “no” to that face. She loves all food. She will hold out on taking a treat if she knows there's something better coming. 

She thinks she is a lap dog, but it doesn’t always work out for her foster mom.  Liv is ok with it not working out for her foster mom; she circles up in her lap anyway.  

Because of her past, she would like to be the Queen bee in her home, with no worries of other dogs being mean to her. 

If you have children they should be older (8 and up) and respectful of animals.  This girl would actually make a great homework buddy.  

If you would like to be considered for adoption, please complete the adoption questionnaire on our website www.heartsofgoldpitrescue.com.  

*2-3 years old
*House trained
*Crate trained
*Needs to be an ONLY dog

animal.description:
Meet Kamen, our 8-9 year old Rottweiller. sadly, 4 years ago Kamen had a drastic weight loss and was over treated with Prednisone. The resulting side effects called calcinosis cutis which he still has and will always have. There is no reversing the effects of this disease but we are doing all we can to make sure it does not progress any farther. ( He looks like he had a turtle shell on his back) Kamen is on a no grain diet with no grain treats. He does well with well behaved children (over 6) other dogs as long as they do not get in his face. He is a wonderful, sweet, totally house trained boy who needs to find the loving home he so richly deserves.

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility..

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Rocky is a handsome male Doberman with cropped ears that do not stand and a docked tail. He was living with another male dog and the two did not get along; since Rocky was the newest member of the family, he was regretfully relinquished.

We have found Rocky to be an initially shy boy especially around women; he seems to prefer men. However, once he warms up he is affectionate and really loves a good butt rub! Rocky has no bad habits: he is not a barker, chewer, or digger. He enjoys going for walks and he is quiet in his crate.

Rocky prefers humans to other dogs. Like most male Dobermans he needs to be the only male dog in the house. Although Rocky did live with kids we think the best home for him would be with a single person or couple who have plenty of time to spend with their dog. Rocky is house-trained and crate-trained and he has a medium energy level. He was born in December of 2016.

They are also crate trained although they have free-roam of the kitchen while their fosters are gone and they haven't had any issues so far. animal.description:
Meet Gus!! He is a 1 1/2 year old beautiful Double Merle Great Dane.  He can hear but has a vision impairment. Because of his size, weighing over 100 lbs, Gus would fit best in a home with older children 12 and up and a family with Dane experience. He is good with other dogs and a fence is recommended.

He loves to cuddle in bed or lounge on the sofa. Gus definitely needs someone that is home a lot, at least in the beginning so he gets used to their scent and being around as he gets acclimated. A quieter home would probably be ideal as he is going to be on high alert in a new surrounding. Once he realized all was well, he would curl back up on the couch. 

Gus will need a family that gives him time to adjust to his new home. Someone that will let Gus come to them when he is ready and not try to force a bond immediately. Someone that is mindful of his eyes and what side he can see out of and remember that when they go to pet him - again, just in the beginning. 

Hes loves to play tug of war and I will give you all his toys (if you want them) but most of the day he just eats and sleeps...even with me being home all day. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption policies and apply online at [www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt).

Visit [www.speakfortheunspoken.com](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/) will give you more information about our rescue.

***PLEASE READ*** WE DO NOT RESPOND TO PETFINDER OR EMAIL INQUIRIES. Please fill out an application on our website if you are interested in adopting this dog. We will only set up a meeting with the dog once you have an approved adoption application. We actively manage our dogs on Petfinder, the dogs listed are available for adoption. We will remove the dog from view once they are pending adoption.

animal.description:
Pug Rescue of New England (PRoNE) is a non-profit 501(c)(3), all volunteer foster home based rescue organization. Available
Puma, 6yr old chihuahua

This little 8.5lb guy looks just like a TEDDY BEAR in person! He has been dosed with a form of CHF (Congestive Heart Failure) which will monitoring and medication for progression. He's super affectionate with grown-ups, and tolerates children, but on his terms. He is learning how to play with the other dogs in his foster home. Puma is more comfortable with small dogs but is aggressive toward the pug, Frenchie, and lab in his foster home. For these reasons, we think he'd do best in an adult only home or with older dog savvy children (8 years or older) and only one or two dogs less than 10 pounds in size.

Puma is the perfect pint-sized travel companion, or couch potato dog. Just don't forget to take him on a few walks each day

Qualifications your home must meet to be considered for adoption:

All children living in or frequently visiting your home must be 8 years of age or over with no likelihood of this changing
Fenced in yard or home without direct outdoor access (to limit risk of Puma running out the door to the yard/street when it is opened - this has happened in Puma's foster home - gates blocking access to front doors is adequate and must be installed at time of home visit)
Only 0-2 other dogs in the home, and all must be less than 10 pounds in size. Puma will resource guard food, humans, toys, and territory but he will also play with dogs smaller than he is.
Chihuahua savvy home accustomed to chi habits such as barking and bonding with one person exclusively
Must be willing to continue housebreaking Puma as he has not fully caught on yet
Must be afford periodic vet visits, medication and continued monitoring of Puma's heart condition.
If you are interested in adopting, your home situation MUST meet this criteria:
A vet reference check, dog walker check (if applicable), landlord check (if applicable), a phone interview and home visit will be conducted prior to approval. If you think a pug is right for your family and you meet the criteria, please apply to adopt on our website at www.pugrescueofnewengland.org.
BE SURE TO REFERENCE THE SPECIFIC PUG!
Our mission is simple: we find homes for abandoned and surrendered pugs in New England. Our pugs will be UTD on shots and spayed or neutered prior to adoption. You must be a resident of New England (New York residents carefully considered).
PRoNE is supported by adoption fees, donations and funds raised through auctions and events. Adoption fees range from $150-$500.
Adoption FAQs: pugrescueofnewengland.org/adopt/adoption-faqsAdoption App: pugrescueofnewengland.org/adopt/adoption-application
Follow us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/PugRescueofNewEngland/

animal.description: Are you seeking a furry friend to keep you company on the couch, or need a buddy to be your companion when you come home from work, or a furry friend to take a short walk routinely......then BUDDY might be the companion for you.   BUDDY is a neutered male, boxer/bulldog/terrier blend...and like all of our fostered kids current on vaccines, heartworm negative, crate trained, house trained, and walks well on leash.   We believe he is around 7 or 8yrs, and 60lbs   BUDDY has a unique personality; he will talk when he has to go "out to potty" or if he just wants outside to meander and nap in the sun.  He enjoys cuddling up in couch corner, OR on top his crate (if there are lots of blankets there),  OR in an easy chair after his walk OR playtime with his favorite toys.  He will bring you his favorite toy in hopes you will play with him for a few minutes THEN he is content to play alone.  At mealtime, he sits politely and drools while you prepare his meals.   BUDDY loves "nose work" the more opportunity for him to SNIFF (hunt) & FIND the more FUN for him when he explores scents in his yard and on his walks!!  Sometimes he shows his stubborn streak when walking IF he feels sniffing and peeing is more important than walking, lol  Buddy LOVES his food and treats....so training is easy with him ;-)  He is very SMART,  he knows Sit, Stay, Leave it, and Here .  His RECALL and OBEDIENCE grows stronger WHEN his trusts grows stronger  with his caretaker; consistent rules and high value (low calorie treats) are important to BUDDY....HE thrives on routine.   BUDDY's curiosity to explore and protect is strong; so, it is best not to leave him unsupervised and unleashed in a yard; he can/could jump a fence IF a dog or cat approaches.    He enjoys his human companions and will give you kisses (ear licks) after he feels you have earned his trust and respect as his loving caretaker.   Buddy would do best as an only dog.  Children 12yrs and older are recommended due to his strength & size.     If interested in BUDDY, send us an adoption application located on the ADOPTME page at Dream4pets.org    We have a 120 mile radius from MIAMI COUNTY for adopting most of our dogs.      If interested in BUDDY, please send us an adoption application found on the ADOPTME page at Dream4pets.org .  or Email Petsrrpassion@gmail.com    Our adoption radius is typically 120 miles from Miami COunty (Troy, Tipp City, Piqua area)

animal.description:
Beautiful blue female looking for a quiet home in the country.  Enjoys evenings by the fireplace, quiet walks in the woods and cuddling with her loved one.  If we were writing a singles ad for our sweet girl that is likely how it would start. There is so much we can tell you about this wonderful dog.  And we know the right home is out there just waiting for her to join them.

Delilah loves long walks and as with any good pittie she just loves everyone she meets. Weighing in at about 70 pounds she could easily be considered a large dog. And she can be pretty strong when walking her on leash with a regular collar. But with a SENSE-sation harness or Gentle Leader Easy Walk Harness she walks very well.


To meet Delilah it is hard to believe that she was originally found tied to a fence in NYC. She was then taken in by someone with 3 dogs and one of them attacked her.  So once she arrived at the shelter she was actually terrified of the other dogs.  But given slowintroductions to a new dog she is does quiet well with them. In fact for quite some time she was even fostered in a home with 3 other dogs.  She has also lived in a home with a cat and would likely do well in a home with a cat that is dog savvy.

Delilah is housebroken and crate trained.  Although she is could likely be left in the house uncrated without any issues.  

We strive very hard to make sure that our dogs are placed in the proper homes.  It is important to us that it is right for the dog as well as the adopter.  So that being said, Delilah does have a few quirks. She sometimes becomes startled at certain objects (when bicycles go by, skateboards, etc) and when she does she is gets a bit jumpy at the end of a leash.  She needs an owner who is going to understand her fear based issues and be ok dealing with them. Continued exposure to these things have not helped so avoidance may be the best option.  That is why we feel that a home in the country where she won’t encounter the sounds and sometimes overwhelming things urban life brings might be best.

As much as we love to see our adopters bring their dogs everywhere with them, in this case we are looking for a laid back home in the country where Delilah can just be herself.  Where she can relax with her people and hang out around the house without the stress of walking on busy streets and encountering things that make her nervous.  So if you live in the country and think you might be just the right spot for Delilah please Fill out our adoption application.  We would love to talk to you!

** Adoption fee $50 – the balance has been sponsored by volunteers who love her **

Hope would love a home where she had a fenced yard to run and play in and a person to love.  She has some dog friends but can be picky so would likely do best as the only dog in the home.  

Hope is crate, leash, and house trained.  

Could you be the home this beauty has been waiting for?  If so, apply today at FYDRadopt.com so we can see if she would be a good fit!  

She is spayed, microshipped, up-to-date on vaccines, and on heartworm preventative.  Her adoption fee is $175.  Please contact us at ForeveryoursOKC@gmail.com if you are interested!

animal.description:
Sweet, loving, handsome boy seeks special home where I can be pampered and spoiled. You see, I was diagnosed with a heart condition last year and things weren't looking so good. I'm much better now and doing great on my heart medications, fish oil, and yummy high quality food. I enjoy lots of loving care with my foster family, but I would really love a family of my own. Are you that special someone that loves older, wiser gentleman needing some extra care?

I mostly ignore other dogs. I prefer easy-going, mellow dogs rather than rowdy dogs that jump on me. I did great with my intro to the office cat. I could share a home with cats as long as they are friendly and well mannered.

When you come to visit be sure and ask for me. I'm the silly boy with the big smile, happily greeting old and new friends that come to visit. I’d love to be your new best friend. I can't wait to meet you!

Benny is about 8 years old, neutered, crate trained and up to date on shots. His heart medication makes him very thirsty and he then needs to pee a lot. Easy access and a dog door to a fenced yard would be ideal for Benny. Also a home where his person is retired or works from home. He is currently staying with SevaDog Rescue. Canine Miracle Rescue and SevaDog Rescue are working together to help Benny find his perfect family.

animal.description: Kasper has gotten pretty comfy at his foster home already and is full of love and young Boxer energy. He is pretty strong on the leash and loves to play so he will need LOTS of exercise and play time to make him happy. A home with a fenced in yard would be best for him. Kasper is said to have formerly lived with a 12 year old child and is very sweet with the 7 year old child in his foster home. He has been reactive when on the leash on walks and doesn't seem to be very socialized with other dogs. Kasper would very likely be happier in a home with no other dogs. He has not been around cats.UPDATE: Kasper will be starting formal training to work on his reactivity with other dogs and to work on some manners and basic obedience. He has been in some training and daycare activities and has done very well with other dogs so far!! UPDATE FROM KASPER'S FOSTER MOM: Kasper is a sweet boy and knows many commands like sit, shake and stay. He loves his toys too. He is high energy and really likes to be near his people. He is reactive with other dogs and lunges at them while on leash. He also barks out the window when he sees other dogs. He has attended doggie daycare and did okay- but not one on one while on leash. He does play rough while at daycare. Kasper is very treat motivated as well. He can be vocal when he wants to play. He is a typical young boxer. 2/2/21 1:49 PM

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Rusty.  I am a handsome fellow who is a German Shepherd mix.  I think I am at least 3 years old.  I am up to date on my vaccines, neutered and heart worm negative.  I am currently being fostered in East Texas about 30 minutes north of Nacogdoches, TX.

I found myself abandoned in Houston, TX during Hurricane Harvey.  I was pretty scared and admit I was not very cooperative with those who were trying to help me get to safety.

I am looking for a family or human who will have lots of patience with me.  I am still a little scared when I meet new people and especially new dogs.  I like people but just need to know that I can trust them.  I also can get a long with other dogs who are calm and submissive.  I need a family who will love me, not make me a backyard ornament, play with me and never abandon me.

I like to run around the yard and chase balls and rope toys.  I can sit and shake.

If you would like to meet me, please contact Penny by texting or calling her @ 713-824-2737 or emailing her @ pennykbryce@gmail.com

Looking forward to hearing from you soon,
Rusty

Hi, there! My name is Glyde, but you can call me Mr. Perfect!

I don't mean to brag –– my manners are way too nice for that –– but if I were a person, I would be the captain of the football team AND the debate club. I'm athletic and clever and just so personable. Or so they tell me!

One thing I don't mind saying about myself is that I aim to please. I'm a great walker –– no pulling on the leash or chasing after squirrels for me! I'm also very gentle when I play.

animal.description: There's something wrong with your couch...it doesn't have Ruby Dee curled up on it. We saved Miss Ruby, our 6ish year old Pitbull mix, from a high kill shelter where she came in as an owner surrender. Like so many dogs we rescue, she contracted an upper respiratory infection, which quickly worsened. Unfortunately, after battling and beating pneumonia, she was diagnosed with chronic lymphocytic leukemia. She then settled in with a new long-term foster and we have been closely monitoring her condition with an oncologist ever since. So far so good because while her leukemia cannot be cured, it is progressing very slowly. Shhhh…don't tell Ruby she's sick because she doesn’t know and you would never know it either. Our 35lb. goofball has a zest for life that is completely contagious and her love for toys may only be rivaled by her obsession with sun bathing. She is all about playing and spending time in the yard on warm days (with supervision of course). Good news -- she is also perfectly content to cuddle up on the couch for a good snuggle session, preferably tucked behind your legs and under a blanket. Our gem of a "pocket pittie" is extremely intelligent and eager to please (she is a “sit, stay, go to your bed” champ) and she will quickly win you over with her signature snorts and snores. Pitbull/Piglet mix? It's possible. While Ruby Dee can be iffy with cats and selective with other pups, her love for people and LIFE make her all the dog you need. Ruby will flourish with an active family (no kiddos please!) who want to take her along on all their adventures and then invite her up on the couch for a nap or movie night. Ruby Dee is housebroken when kept on a schedule, crate trained, spayed, vaccinated, heartworm negative and microchipped. Despite her diagnosis, we do not feel Ruby is a hospice dog and anticipate she has many wonderful years ahead of her. Stop staring at your empty sofa! Ruby's ready and waiting! Apply at omdrescue.org
animal.name: Ruby Dee

animal.description:
Meeko is a four year old, bi-eyed boy ready for a husky saavy home of his own.  He came into rescue as an owner surrender two years ago.  Meeko was purchased as a pup, and in the two years he was with his original family his upper canines were pulled.  

Although there was another dog in the home Meeko did not know how to "dog." He would greet other dogs with piloerect fur while barking in their face.  His barking was more so stranger danger than aggression; Meeko never pushed past that point.  However it was no way for him to "win friends and influence strangers."

Meeko plays well with other dogs.  He is a little boisterous when he becomes excited.  He does occassionally have anxiety when crated; we use a Vari Kennel Ultra with a couple of black trucker bungees in the front tie down holes. Meeko would do best in an active, patient, home with a husky companion, and a physically fenced yard.  We will not place Meeko in a home with children as he was very distrustful of the child in his home.

For additional information or an adoption application please email... kaleidoscopek9s@yahoo.com

animal.description:
Awesome Elliot,  an approximate 3 year old, HANDSOME, SWEET, STAFFORDSHIRE TERRIER, is a sweet boy! Look how proud he is sitting up in his picture and a cute personality!
Elliot was rescued from the Stanislaus shelter up by the Paradise fires who  begged LBWF to help save Elliot! They loved him and so do we. He is an easy dog. He passed his temp tests up at the shelter but due to the large pet overpopulation and fire victims the shelter has no room!
We love Elliot - he is a sweetheart! He came in way underweight probably out on his own for far too long after the fires and no one claimed him. Many animals have not had their families recover them as they have no homes!. We are working to get him to gain weight in a healthy way..
He is very gentle natured, which is so great for those looking for the CHILL GUY!   He is calm, doesnt bark or cry, causes no trouble, sweet and is looking for his forever home! . He has a beautiful blue coat , from tip to tail, little wrinkles on his forehead that are so cute. He loves you to sit and pet his head and body! 
 Hes awesome and will make a great new family member for the holiday .
 He wasnt given much time at the shelter for someone to adopt him, which is the case now a days, so LBWF stepped up and boy are we so glad to help this gentle angel!
He is so sweet and easy! Loving and sweet and adorable personality  
  He has met several dogs here through the fence and is a cool guy. We are just letting him rest after his last few months..He is doing awesome! He is very sweet, easy and active. He wants to live life, full of travel, friends, the beach, camping and fun times! HE IS a perfect age to blend right into the family!  He has the potential to be all you are looking for in your forever family companion! He will make a great friend, will love the beach, camping and lots of activities. 
up to date on shots, micro chipped, neutered
PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION on our website to book your appointment to meet Elliot and friends at www.LindaBlairWorldheart.org and see many of our adoptable dogs.
Come meet Elliot and friends at the LBWF rescue property in ACTON, CA where the dogs enjoy large play yards and love!
Follow us on Facebook/Linda Blair Worldheart Foundation
Twitter and Instagram@LindaBlairWF
Your donations help us save CA pets lives

animal.description: 2- 3 year old Louie came to us with a history of being a "bait dog" for dog fighters.  That may or may not be true as Louie does seem to have some neurological issues which could have been caused by injury (head bobbing when drinking, and some peripheral vision issues).  We have had Louie thoroughly checked out by our veterinarian, and he has assured us that though Louie does seem to have some strange issues, none of them appear to be affecting his current health in any way nor does he expect them to affect him in the future.  Louie really doesn't care for the company of other dogs - he would much rather be an "only furchild".  He is very well behaved on leash.  He can be affectionate with his humans once he gets to know them, but can be a bite risk to those he does not know or trust.  Louie needs someone with a LOT of patience and knowledge of dog behaviors to adopt him and show him just how good a dog's life can be, therefore,  Louie would do best in a home with an experienced dog owner/trainer, and absolutely no children.  Louie is a work in process - and his new family should regard him as a piece of art that when finally complete will dazzle all who meet him.  If you would like to offer Louie a forever home, please submit an application which you can find on our website (www.almostheaven-golden-retriever-rescue.org)

animal.description:
Estimated age: 3
Weight: 40 pounds 
House & crate trained

Hi, my name is Owen! Let me tell you my story....

I was living life on the streets when I was just a pup, until one day when I ran out in front of my foster mom's car by Owen Rd. I was seriously 
emaciated- nothing but skin and bones....and I had tons of icky worms.

Foster mom scooped me up and put me in her car and she did a "stray hold" to see if anyone was missing me. Of course, nobody was. I had been alone for a while. 

Foster mom soon realized that I had a rough beginning, when I saw dogs bigger than me I would shake with fear. She thinks I had to compete for food with bigger dogs when I was alone and they scare me now. Because of this, I would prefer being someone's one and only furbaby!

I am 3 years young. I'm a petite little pittie at 40 pounds. I love doing things and going on adventures! Foster mom has taken me hiking, I enjoyed it. 
I also love to zoom zoom in backyard. I think I would love to run with a human! Stuffy toys are my favorite and I am the master of destuffing.

I love humans of all sizes. I love giving everyone I meet a hug & a sloppy kiss!

I am seeking a home where:
- Humans will crate me when they are away
- I can get mental and physical exercise
- Training is incorporated into my life
- I am the one and only fur baby (no kitty cats, no dogs)
- Not looking to go to the dog park/dog bar

Before emailing- please read:
- Yes, this dog is available for adoption
- The adoption fee for Owen is $256
- Apply at c2cnd.org
- The adoption fee covers their age appropriate shots, microchip, deworming, spay/neuter, and any other medical expenses while in our care.
- Local adopters only. Due to our thorough adoption process including home visits, we limit our adoptions to local families in the greater Charlotte area.
- If you have any additional questions, email us at dogs@c2cnd.org and we will respond as soon as possible!

Skywalker is a handsome 5 year old guy. He loves taking long walks and is very affectionate with everyone he meets. This boy is super mellow and trots along on his walks just taking in the world around him. Skywalker is always down with some quality time with you just to hang and gives out some kisses. He is such a snuggle monster.

Sky loves his toys, and would do best in a home without younger children as he doesn't always know how to share them. He would love someone who understands him, and has some experience as a dog owner. Our Sky really just wants to have a person he can call his own. Fill out our dog adoption application online at pawscrossedny.org to meet this dreamy Jedi. 

*Skywalker is on a training plan and requires more than one visit with our Behavior team. If you are interested in meeting Skewalker, please contact us at adoptions@pawscrossedny.org for more information!*

Before you can adopt sweet Skywalker, please complete an adoption application on our website at pawscrossedny.org! Once your application is approved, you will receive a link to schedule an appointment online. If you have any questions about Skywalker, please email us at adoptions@pawscrossedny.org for more information. Please understand we cannot hold any pet. All adoptions are done on a first come, first adopt basis for approved applicants.

The Shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

Courtesy Posting on 12/22/18.  Pictures and video taken 12/16/18.  VALENTINE IS NEEDING TO BE RE-HOMED.  This is a courtesy posting for Brandy, who lives in the Bullard, TX area. Please e-mail Brandy at shadowgathering13@gmail.com if you're interested in adopting Valentine after reading his profile.  Dog breed pictures don't positively identify what breed(s) Valentine is without a DNA test.  His body slightly resembles a Greyhound body, and his head and ears resemble a Terrier breed.

Brandy found Valentine as a puppy around 6 months old so she doesn't know his history before finding him, really loves him, and will continue to care for him until she can find just the right home for him that can spend more time with him. He spends a lot of time in his outside kennel during her long work hours, and she wants a better quality of life for him. He is 3 to 4 years old, current on vaccinations as of 11/22/18, heartworm negative, knows basic commands, and is neutered. He is protective of his property from people and other dogs while inside the fence of his property. Off his property, his behavior is not as protective, and would be a good guard dog for someone with no children. He does require a secure fenced yard. He is good with a few other dogs that he lives with, and a dog down the road. He might be good with other dogs once he gets to know them, but his initial reaction to new people and dogs is defensive. It's not always the same; just situational.

$50 adoption fee.

animal.description:
Trooper was found under an overpass in Fresno in a box full of water. He was painted purple, and unable to use his back end...had obvious injuries. So a good Samaritan reached out to us to help. Our vet found two bullets in him. One in his leg which they were able to remove and another lodged in his spine, which was causing the paralysis. We then took him to a neurologist at UC Davis, where Dr Toyota confirmed that he was permanently paralyzed due to the location of the bullet and that surgery or therapy would not help this. So the vets left the bullet.
He will come with his cart and his drag bag but he gets around great as is.
****PLEASE DO NOT CALL TO CHECK STATUS OF A DOG...PHONE CALLS ARE FOR EMERGENCIES ONLY. EMAIL US WITH ANY QUESTIONS ON ADOPTION AS WE DO NOT GET BACK TO PHONE CALLS ABOUT ADOPTION.
Shots up to date (DHPP), wormed, micro chipped, altered (spayed/neutered). We also now give one free vet visit with our local vet within first 3 days of adoption!!
Adoption cost for this dog is $150
We are a rescue, and although we have a facility in Modesto most of our dogs/pups are currently being fostered in or around our area. So please be willing to make the trip to see them if you are from out of the area. Our adoption process REQUIRES that an application must first be submitted and approved prior to meeting any of our pets. Just note that we may get several responses on one pet at a time so just because you have an approved application does not mean said pet is on hold for you. One must FIRST confirm an appointment to meet the pet after an approved application has been sent. To inquire about this specific pet, please write to info@pupznpalz.org for an application. Please remember to put the pets name in the subject line when emailing, and on the top on the application. It helps us to help you that must faster. We are a group of volunteers, and ask that you please bare with us. We will get to each person just as quickly as we can. If you do not hear back from us within 24 hours, please send another request as we have been having problems with e-mail.
email: info@pupznpalz.org and ask for an application for which dog you are interested in
phone: 209-480-8662 (9-6 pm only please, cell phone, emergencies only please...do not call to ask status of dog, email please)
**ADOPTION EVENTS: typically every Sat at Modesto Petco 2021 Evergreen Ave from 12-3
**OUR FACILITY: Located at 1430 Carpenter Lane Suite B (by appointment only as we do not have set hours)

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Maynard was just 3 months old when he, his mom Violet, and two siblings were picked up by animal control in rural Oklahoma. They were picked up from a property where they were in the pasture with goats. Animal control had to use a "catch-pole" to catch them because the whole little family was showing a fair amount of fear-based aggression. Sadly, the animal control officer made the decision to euthanize one puppy, saying s/he was too aggressive. It's really hard to imagine a 3-month old puppy being so aggressive that an experienced person couldn't have dealt with the issue, but seeing that the "shelter" was willing to put down a puppy, one local person volunteered to foster Violet and her remaining two puppies until she could find a rescue to take them in.

When we brought them here, the puppies (whom we named Nell and Maynard) were very frightened, and they tried to avoid my attempts to touch them, but they were never aggressive. They simply acted like feral pups who had ZERO experience with humans, other than their very unfortunate interaction with animal control.

Maynard and his sister Nell are in a foster home where they are making slow progress in accepting humans. They enjoy playing with the family's Great Pyrenees and are much more relaxed with HER than with humans.

If you have the patience and compassion to love Maynard and work with him to overcome his difficult start in life, please complete the application on our website at www.bluebonnetrescue.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Violet is a bit of a mystery to us -- from her breed/s to her history, there's a lot more that we DON'T know than we DO know. We DO know that Violet was picked up by animal control in rural Oklahoma, along with three puppies who were estimated to be 3 months old. They were picked up from a property where they were in the pasture with goats. Animal control had to use a "catch-pole" to catch them because the whole little family was showing a fair amount of fear-based aggression. Sadly, the animal control officer made the decision to euthanize one puppy, saying s/he was too aggressive. It's really hard to imagine a 3-month old puppy being so aggressive that an experienced person couldn't have dealt with the issue, but seeing that the "shelter" was willing to put down a puppy, one local person volunteered to foster Violet and her remaining two puppies until she could find a rescue to take them in.

When we brought them here, the puppies (whom we named Nell and Maynard) were very frightened, and they tried to avoid my attempts to touch them, but they were never aggressive. They simply acted like feral pups who had ZERO experience with humans, other than their very unfortunate interaction with animal control. Violet, on the other hand, showed a fair amount of aggression any time I approached the kennel and dog run where I put her together with her puppies. When it came time to take her to the vet for her spay surgery, I was able to get a leash on Violet and take her to the vet. From that point forward, Violet stayed in the house and was not returned to the area where her puppies stayed until they, too, were old enough for spay/neuter surgery. Once she was no longer protecting her pups, Violet settled in to life as a couch potato, and she acted so comfortable that we felt sure she must have had a home at some point in her history. Perhaps she lived in the house with her first family, but then was dumped out in the country when she got pregnant, and turned into a semi-feral dog, doing whatever it took to take care of her little family. She has become very protective of our home, and is not AT ALL welcoming to visitors -- she barks almost non-stop and will nip at strangers. If we have visitors, we typically put Violet in a crate in another room, which is something we do with a few dogs who are so protective of home and family that they don't like visitors. Dogs such as Violet typically do fine when they leave our home -- Violet behaved very nicely at the vet's office, and I am confident that she can transfer her affection to a new family.

Violet is VERY playful, and gets along with all the dogs in our home. One of her favorite play mates is a smaller dog who is about half her size. She also plays with dogs of her own size, and she doesn't discriminate based on gender.

As for her breed/s, we've just made a guess based on her looks, size, protective nature, and the fact that she was living with goats. She is NOT a livestock guardian, but we think it's possible that she is at least part Great Pyrenees. The red ticking in her white coat reminds us of a Red Heeler, but her stout frame and the curl of her tale make us think of an Akita. She has a BIG bark, so whatever her ancestry may be, she definitely acts like a guardian for her home and human family. She would be a great companion and protector for a single person who lives a quiet life without a lot of visitors.

If Violet sounds like exactly the dog for you, please complete the application on our website at www.bluebonnetrescue.org.

animal.description: Dash is nine years old and a joy to be around. His daddy fell on hard times and had to surrender this sweet boy.  Dash loves everyone and gets along great with the pugs in his foster home.  He does need eye meds twice a day to keep his eyes moist and gets a daily supplement for his arthritis. His  back end is a bit wonky but he  gets where  he wants to go just fine.  He loves to be with his human and one of his favorite spots is on the back of the sofa when his human sits down.  Dash frequently will suck on a stuffed toy and fall asleep with it.   He also likes to sleep with his human and will get under the covers at times. He has good house manners but you need to go out with him to be sure he goes potty.  Because of his arthritis and back end issues, Dash will sometimes leak but a belly band helps with that.  Although Dash will go into a crate, it is not his favorite thing to do.  Dash is going to make some lucky family a perfect new member.

animal.description:
Cupid is an almost 3 year old girl who needs a home with someone who has time and patience for training. She didn't get much of that in her previous home, so she's essentially a great big puppy who hasn't learned all the ins and outs of manners. Cupid is incredibly smart and very motivated by treats as well as attention from people. She's eager to please, but needs clear instructions on what's expected of her. Being a very young and active dog, her new home should be ready to give her plenty of physical activity as well as mental stimulation. Cupid is going to take some patience, but she is SO worth it. She gives excellent hugs and has a great smile! At this point in her training, she needs to find a home without children, cats, or small animals. She never learned the proper ways to interact with other dogs, and her attempts at play can be seen as rude. With someone who is willing to work with her in the beginning, she could very well learn to be happy to have another big dog as a friend.


Please give the shelter a call at 508-586-2053 between 1:00 and 4:00 any day except Monday or Wednesday, or email info@apcsm.org to get more information about this pet and our adoption process. Please note- the shelter is closed to walk-through-traffic at this time. Meets are scheduled with an adopter after speaking with an adoption counselor, and an application has been approved for a particular animal.

animal.description:
Ariel - Cocker/Border Collie Mix - Female - 4 Years - www.twyla.org

If you'd like to know more about this dog please visit our website at www.Twyla.org

Meet Princess Ariel! She is a gorgeous 20 pound Cocker/Border Collie mix, and about 4 years old.  Princess Ariel is back with us after a failed adoption due to no fault of hers OR the adopter, we learn more about each dog as their environment changes and we learned that Ariel needs an experienced adopter. She is a little pushy and likes to resource guard, but corrects well when her human calmly but assertively "takes charge".

Princess Ariel is a champion snuggeler and wants nothing else but a cuddle buddy to hang out with all day long. She is looking for a home that has the time and patience to give her the attention she needs and craves. She could live with another dog as long as her human stays "in charge", but would do best as an only dog. It does take her some time to warm up to new people and she is not a fan of kids, so an adult only home or teenage kids or up would be best.

Ariel is looking for a dog-experienced home, preferably as an only dog and no kids. Ariel can be vocal around strangers, so she may not be a good fit for apartment living. We are happy to provide guidance on her training, she has been working with one of our trainers and continuing that training would be vital to her success in a new home. 

***** Please note that not every dog comes to every adoption day, so if you would like to meet a specific dog on adoption day, please contact us so we can make arrangements accordingly. 

Adoption Application are available at: http://www.twyla.org/adopt/adoption-application

animal.description:
Reacher is a wonderful senior Chocolate Lab with a happy spirit even after a rough life!  We are estimating his age at 8 - 10 years old.  Reacher was taken to the county shelter after his owner passed away and no one wanted him.  He was there almost 6 weeks until a special lady came to his rescue!  He has had surgery to remove several fatty tumors, is now on joint supplements and a healthy diet.  His improvement and increase in energy is amazing.  Reacher loves to play ball, of course he has to be limited since he will keep on going!  He enjoys going for walks and most of all he loves being with people.  This is one happy guy now that life is good!  He appears to be smiling all of the time and eager to play a game of tug with his favorite toy.  We are working on a weight loss program to get his weight down, he is now about 80 pounds and doing great!  Reacher is a very special guy with so much love to give!
Reacher has been neutered, is up to date on all vaccinations, tested negative for heartworms and is on monthly prevention.  He will be microchipped prior to adoption.
For more information on Reacher, our adoption process and to complete an application, please contact us by email at allaboutdogscr@gmail.com or visit our website allaboutdogscr.com

animal.description:
My name is Holly and I was rescued from a central valley shelter.  The shelter wanted to euthanize me because of my severe skin allergies but I was saved because my rescuers knew they could help heal me and help me stay well.  I have spent the last year working so hard to find out what I'm allergic to and what I need to eat and what medicines to take to keep my skin comfortable.  I'm considered a bit of a "special needs" pup because I must stay on a special formulation of food and I require monthly medications, but I'm normal in every other way.  I'm just a sweet girl that wants to be loved. I am about 5 years old. 

I really, really love my humans. I could follow you around all day long and give you so much attention and affection. I am hopeful someone wants to invite me into their lives and help me stay well.  I am smaller sized pittie at only about 50 lbs and I am crate trained so I'm easily managed in the house. I find cats to be too tempting though so I should be in a home without any felines.  


Note: While we helped Holly heal on the outside, we have also invested in training for her to help her feel safe and secure on the inside and not be so afraid of other dogs.  She is doing remarkably well as she has built up her confidence and is able to play nicely with other dogs and make friends.  Holly will do best with a dog savvy handler who will understand her and continue to provide her a safe and secure environment.  

Please note that we will provide financial support to her new adopter/family to ensure her health routine for the very best future possible.
