Good With Cats: unknown
Good With kids: yes
Age: Approx. 3 year
Adoption Fee: $350
Fee Includes: Current vaccinations, micro chip, and altered
Harry came to Emotional Rescue about a year and a half ago. It is believed that he was beaten until his back was broken. His owners brought Harry and his brother to a shelter where they were both going to be put to sleep. They believed Harry was unadoptable and his brother would be too sad without him. They were both rescued and Harry quickly took to his wheelchair. His brother happily found a family of his own.
Harry is part Golden Retriever and is about 3 years old.
Harry has a strong personality. He is confident in his adorableness and rightly believes that everyone should love him at first sight. He is a strong believer in getting kisses and hugs before being put to bed and insists on it. 
Harry needs a fenced in yard so he can run fill tilt in his wheels. He currently lives on a farm with a nature trail where he runs laps, digs in the woods and chases the farm animals whenever possible.
Harry requires daily care. He needs a bath at least once a day as he does not have control of his bathroom functions. He loves diapers. Not to wear, just to rip up and shred. He also loves to take diapers off his other wheelie friends. He's a bit of a rascal that way.
Harry weighs about 60 pounds. Potential adopters will need to lift him for baths and to help him in and out of his wheel chair.
Harry loves people of all sizes. Kids 12 years and up, who are fast movers would be best (and no small dogs) because Harry drives his wheels as if he learned from playing Grand Theft Auto. He runs over everyone that doesn't get out of his way. He loves whipping Louies (Doughnuts?) In the snow and mud. He strongly believes that he's living the dream and he's full of joy.
There is a certain amount of work that goes along with caring for Harry (And I mean work of the poop cleaning variety) but he is quite a remarkable dog that bring happiness and laughter.
This pup does not have control of bathroom functions.  Baths will be required daily and Living area will have to be created, such as in a play pen where there is soft bedding that can be changed out  couple times a day.
To meet Harry, apply at emotionalrescuemn.org.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Our precious girl Willow is a female Pit mix girl born in approximately December 2017 and rescued in Texas. Poor Willow found herself alone and scared at a very high kill shelter suffering from serious burns down her back. Rescue Dogs Rock NYC pulled Willow out as soon as we saw her and she immediately received the medical care she required. Fast forward, and Willow is a sweet girl with a big, funny personality who loves to play with her toys. Willow is housebroken, walks nicely on a leash and knows basic commands. She loves to cuddle and sleep under the covers. Willow is a rough and tumble girl and would do best in a home with older children as she can be jumpy. She loves her bones and is sometimes a bit protective of them. Willow is not a fan of cats and would be happier as the only dog in her forever home. Willow needs a special someone to come along, fall in love, and be patient with her as she grows and gains confidence and forgets all about her horrible past. Are you the lucky one that can give this beautiful girl the wonderful life that she is so deserving of?! She is friendly with people of all ages, up to date on vaccinations and will be spayed prior to joining in her forever home. If you would like to give Willow her happy ever after, please fill out an adoption application for her here! Http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

animal.description:
Nickie is a sweet dog that is calm and humble. He interacts with both people and other dogs in a gentle fashion. There is not a mean bone in his body and he is not at all aggressive. If pushed by an assertive dog, he may protect himself with a small snap, but it’s a one and done warning to treat him more respectfully. He prefers to spend time with other dogs rather than by himself and tries to sneak on their pillow with them to take a snooze. He doesn’t understand if they are less than welcoming since he is so friendly to all dogs that he meets. For Nickie, each dog he meets is instantly part of his circle of friends even if the affection is not returned. He keeps trying to teach them that together is better.

Nickie is trying to learn the house rules. It seems a little hard for him to grasp the concepts since he apparently spent the first 6 years of his life without much guidance or supervision. He is trying to master “go potty outside”, “sit” and “off” for starters, and is slowly progressing in his education. The fact that he loves all training treats is a strong positive. He doesn’t have some of the more negative puppy behaviors like chewing on everything or racing around aggravating everyone, but rather enjoys just being near to his family (people and dogs). Of an evening, he is happy to spend time on your lap while watching TV.

When he arrived in rescue, he had a respiratory infection, and needed a little time to recoup. Now he is over that, but he has had two seizures. We have started anti-seizure medication and hope it will control the condition. Other than that, he is healthy and happy. We feed Nickie in a crate because he is always ravenous, and I doubt he would respect the “your food and my food” concept. He is currently underweight and is thin as a rail. We hope to fatten him up a little, but I believe he may have a slightly sensitive stomach, although this is hard to evaluate with all the vetting he has undergone in two short weeks. Now that the initial round of vetting is complete, we will be able to assess his digestive issues if there are any. Once he has a chance to settle down and relax, his digestion may improve.

Nicki is a little shy when he first meets you. This is a result of his past treatment (which is a mystery to us) and all the changes we have made to his life in the last 2.5 weeks (dogs don’t generally like change). I believe Nickie is extremely brave to survive with his personality intact since he was dropped off in the night repository at the shelter without much ado. It has to be traumatic to be wisked up and dropped off at a totally new and unknown place without any indication that some kind person would provide care. For this reason, I’m not surprised that loud voices and noises startle him, quick movements can frighten him and it takes some time for him to trust enough to wag his tail for folks. The tip of his tail by the way has a kink in it. We are not sure if he was born that way or if it was broken in his previous life. His tail doesn’t appear painful, but it does seem a little sensitive.

Nicki does like to play with other dogs at a slower pace than the frantic puppy mode, and he will chew on flexible nylbones for entertainment. He is crate trained, but needs some to work on walking with a lead. If you have a gentle dog looking for companionship, please contact BRSM about Noodles Nicholas Charles. He can be your best friend as well as your dog’s best friend. 

Noodle's Webpage - http://beaglemaryland.org/brsm_ms/vIndividualCurrentDog.aspx?dogid=69678
Adoptable Dog Webpage - http://beaglemaryland.org/brsm_ms/vCurrentDogs.aspx

If you'd like to adopt one of our beagles:
*Go to our Website - href="http://beaglemaryland.org
*Review our  Standards for Adoption - http://beaglemaryland.org/Home.aspx?pg=standardsforadoption.htm
*Fill out an Adopter Profile - http://beaglemaryland.org/new_site/documents/adopterprofilenew.htm
 and email it to us (or print it off, fill it in and send it via regular mail, if you prefer)
*A BRSM volunteer will contact you to guide you through the rest of the process!

We hope to hear from you, and so do the beagles!

animal.description:
Tess is a beautiful 2 year old German Shepherd who weighs about 60 lbs.  She is spayed, up to date on shots, micro chipped, on heartworm and flea and tick prevention.  We expect that she will be a large sized dog when full grown (check out those paws)!

You may have also noticed the she is wearing a diaper.  That is because she is a special needs dog now likely at the hands of a cruel individual.  We suspect that she received some trauma when she was 6-8 weeks old (likely kicked) and of course received no vet care at the time of the incident.  Then she found herself in the shelter when just 3 months old.  The shelter had her broken tail amputated and had her spayed, but didn't realize her other injury.

We have been to the vet and there is nothing that can done to repair the nerve damage.  This will be a lifelong condition.  She is bowel incontinent (meaning she can't control her fecal output).  She has full functioning bladder control. 

I am not adopting her out to be an outside dog.  Period.  She is a beautiful girl who didn't ask for any of this and deserves to be an inside dog and live with a family.  She lives in my home. .  She will not be a lawn ornament.  No small children due to her puppy nature and antics.  Her "special needs" take me less then 15 minutes a day of extra time versus a regular dog. She does very well at keeping herself clean and I have covers on my furniture that are easily washable..  If you don't think she is worth an extra 15 minutes of your time a day, please move on to the next dog, because I can assure you she is worth every second of it!

Please don't apply for Tess out of pity for her, that would not be fair to her.  We are looking for the right family who understand what her special need is and what it will take to offer her a lifetime of care and support.  I know this may not be quick or easy .. and that is fine.  Tess is just fine living with me in my home, learning how to be an inside dog until the right family comes along.  She is perfect in every other way. She is smart, silly and a regular pup who loves to play, chase and chew toys!  She gets along with the other dogs in the home and has full run of the house with access to the back yard.  You must have a physically fenced yard, no exceptions.  

If you are serious about wanting to offer Tess a forever inside home, then please contact me at info@safehaventn.com and/or fill out the adoption application on our website www.safehaventn.com.  We will offer a 2 week trial adoption period to an approved adopter so you have a chance to fully realize what is involved in offering her a permanent place in your family. 

Thank you for taking the time to read about this gorgeous girl, and if she is not the right fit for you, please share her profile so that the right family has a chance to find her!

animal.description:
**NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE**  ... We are so busy with rescuing and caring for animals and can't return everyone's inquiry.  If you are interested in adopting this pet...You must fill out the adoption application at:  
http://www.marlcares.org/adopt_app-dog.php   (cut and paste into your browser) 
PLEASE READ all the following info.  We do not reply to inquiries asking if the dog is still available, if it is listed here, then it is still available.   

Maddy's owners had to give her up because they lived in a town that had a breed ban...they did not allow pitbulls.  A neighbor reported them for having a pitbull and when the police came to take her and euthanize her...the owners wouldn't let them in and then late that night drove her  to someone who got to us.   Maddy lived with other dogs large and small and cats.  Her dad was a truck driver so she frequently went on long road trips with him....so she is always ready for a car ride and loves it and is a well mannered passenger.  She loves toys and balls.  She loves to cuddle and will snuggle in under the covers at night and keep your toes warm.  Maddy is very affectionate and very well behaved.  She loves everyone she meets and everyone loves her.  Maddy loves to play with other dogs and curl up with them when it is nap time.  Maddy was born Aug 5th 2017.  Maddy loves to play tug with other dogs.  Maddy is looking for a home that will love her and make her their BFF.

$150 adoption fee, spayed/neutered, microchipped, current vaccinations, and currently kennel trained.

ADOPTION APPLICATION:  If you are interested in this pet you must fill out the Adoption Application…which you can find on this site or you can copy and paste this link … http://www.marlcares.org/adopt_app-dog.php    
This does not obligate you in any way.  If this does not work for you then you can email us at midsouthpets@aol.com for one.

PLEASE DO NOT CONTACT US BEFORE READING THE FOLLOWING INFO: 
Your inquiry may not get a reply if you have not read the info we have taken the time to provide. PLEASE READ about our ADOPTION PROCESS AND REQUIREMENTS provided on this site before contacting us. You can find it quickly by clicking on our NAME or MORE ABOUT US in the column to the right of this pet’s description. All your questions can be answered by reading the following info provided below. Our pets are fostered in the Memphis Area, a tri-state area, TN/AR/MS. Most are fostered in Red Banks, MS. 

We do not allow meetings with any of our dogs until we have your Adoption Application. Adopting a new family member should involve a well-thought out and deliberate process. This is not an impulse purchase. Please understand that we do not want these animals to be homeless again. We try to complete the process as quickly as possible and appreciate all the applications and will consider each and every one we receive. 

Filling out the Adoption Application does not obligate you in any way, but simply tells us a little bit about you and whether you and this pet would be a good fit for each other. We will call you after we receive your application and answer all your questions and talk to you about this pet. After being approved, we will set up a time to bring the pet to meet you and your family and pets or set up a time for you to meet the pet at the foster home.

NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE. Rescue is a full time job every day. Please know because we are so very busy with the dogs along with processing applications, updating webpage’s, rescuing, in many vet appointments, caring for seniors and hospice dogs, etc, etc that we are not able to return phone calls or emails asking if this dog is still adoptable, how much is it to adopt, is it house trained etc…We have included all the info we have on this dog at this current time and update the bio as we learn more about them. We kennel train all the dogs and will indicate if there are housebreaking issues that we have discovered. We update our site regularly so if the dog is listed here they are in fact adoptable, but may have applications coming in on them, so if you are interested, you need to get your application in now.

**WE RESERVE THE RIGHT TO REFUSE ANY ADOPTION** Our first concern is the happiness and welfare of the animal. We respect our potential adoptors and appreciate your interest in adopting one of our pets. We care about you too and that you are getting the right fit for your home and lifestyle. By following our process, together we can make sure you are getting the right pet.**

NOTE: We prefer to adopt in the Mid-South AREA, usually no more than 1-2 hours away in driving distance. It is up to the foster home, how far they are willing to drive. We rarely adopt long distance, but will consider each and every application. 

MidSouth Animal Rescue League is an all breed, 501c3, non-profit organization that prefer to rescue senior dogs and special cases. WE LOVE ROTTWEILERS...With 20 years of experience with our beloved ROTTWEILER breed, and little help for this breed in our area, we try to focus on rescuing them and try not to ever have to turn any away that need us…especially the seniors that end up in shelters. Currently, we have several senior rottweilers in our hospice foster program. We always need more fosters so that we never have to say NO to them or other seniors. 

We have also started a community relief effort specifically in the Red Banks, MS area not far from us, called The Dog House Project, where we go door to door providing dog houses to dogs on chains and other dogs and cats without proper shelter, including straw in cold temps, as well as food and other supplies as needed. We offer free spay/neuter services to those animals and continue to check on them all year. To date many have been spayed and neutered and some have been surrendered from their neglected lives on chains. We are making a difference and need your donations to continue this program. We always need igloo type dog houses. 

MidSouth Animal Rescue League relies on the kindness, generosity, and financial support of people like you so that we can continue to rescue and care for dogs like this one. We are a group of dedicated volunteers who respond to animals in need in shelters, strays, and from individuals. We receive no federal or state funds and are supported solely by private donations. 

Many of the animals we save are in need of special medical care or surgery to bring them back to health before they can be placed. Veterinary care, vaccinations, tests, x-rays, medications, spay and neutering, heartworm prevention, flea/tick prevention, worming, food, kennels, grooming, and other supplies are provided for each dog while in our care.

Jolie needs a fenced in yard or a very active person family to keep her physically and mentally exercised. She walks great on a leash and would love activities such as hiking and exploring. Jolie needs her own person and/or Family to help her blossom to her true potential. She is spayed and UTD on her vaccines, micro-chipped and current with monthly heart worm preventive. Jolie is a dog who will need to be inside with you and outside for physical and mental stimulation. We will only consider homes that make their dog(s) a part of the family.

animal.description:
You’re in for a treat when you meet me!  I am a WORLD full of fun!  I absolutely love to cuddle with humans of all sizes.  My  favorite playtime involves chasing my beloved basket ball - you throw it and I’ll go around the GLOBE get it, or playing in the water hose!  

Humans seem to really like me because I am well-behaved and house-trained.  I’ve met other animals called cats, and they give me a fright, so I won’t be comfortable with them in a house. And I'm pretty picky with other dogs, so it's probably best I get to be the king of my castle by being the only pet.

I am neutered, which means “very good boy” according to the nice veterinarian I met.  That vet also gave me a microchip, a flu shot, heart-worm test, and all my vaccinations.  
I have my own harness and leash and I even have 30 days of free health insurance when you adopt me!  I am such a good boy, I convinced them to enter my adoptive family in a $500 gift card drawing, which will buy LOTS of toys for our playtime together. 

I am accepting applications for fur-parents now. If you’d like to meet me, drop me a line at adopt@nokill-louisville.com or fill out the adoption form at https://www.nokill-louisville.org/adopt

animal.description:
Georgie is around 5-6 years old and weighs 13 pounds. He has the most adorable curly tail! He was abandoned at the home of a family who is known for taking in unwanted dogs in Colton. They surrendered him to us to find him a forever home. He is quiet and low-maintenance once settled in. He is pretty independent as well. He seems more feline than canine in nature. He has a medium energy level and is not hyper. He does not require a yard, though if he does have a yard or patio, it must be secure for him (no holes or gaps for him to slip out of). He is a timid dog and would do best in a calm home with NO CHILDREN OR VISITORS. He needs an adopter that will understand that Georgie would not do best interacting with people he does not know. He will bark and move away from strangers; he does not want to be pet by strangers. He is sociable and friendly with other small/medium-sized dogs, male or female. He is intimidated by big doggies though and would not be the best match for a household that has a big dog. He would not be suitable for dog parks/beaches due to the higher stress levels and unpredictability of the other dogs or people there. Georgie enjoys the company of humans, but similar to some cats, he does enjoy his independence. He is sweet, though not outwardly affectionate, with his family. Nevertheless, he will require a PATIENT adopter who is willing to let him adjust at his own pace without expecting too much from him too soon. His adopters must be willing to give him space and have patience not to smother him with affection/attention or try to pick him up when he is not ready yet. He would not be a good candidate for inexperienced adopters. He is crate-trained and knows how to use a doggy door. For more information about Georgie, please give his foster mom, Lydia, a call at 714-357-8405. His adoption fee is $225 and covers the cost of his neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchip and microchip registration. If you’d like to be considered for adoption, the first step is completing an application which is available on our website, poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab. Please read the below paragraphs for more information on our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered. 

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in,  please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

Rosey
Available for adoption through our regular adoption program or our seniors for seniors program
Pit bull
About 8 years old
House trained
Crate trained
Knows all of her basic commands and more
Needs to be an only pet
GREAT with children!!!

Rosey was adopted from us in 2015, and sadly was returned earlier in 2018 because of a family situation in which they absolutely could not keep her. She is a well-mannered, loving, happy, wonderful dog who will make an absolutely AWESOME family pet! Rosey means a lot to all of us at FFFR and we want to see her settled in a wonderful forever home as soon as possible. She is a very special girl.

Since coming back to us in 2018, Rosey has had surgery on both knees - she tore the ACL's in both of them and had a torn meniscus in addition.  She is completely healed from the surgeries and is back to being her happy, active self.

She also has had a surgery to remove a mass from her foot.  It turned out to be a sarcoma - low grade, of a kind that generally is not metastatic and has a low chance of recurrence.  She should be fine and we don't anticipate any regrowth.

Rosey also has skin allergies and is on medication for those.

In spite of all of that, Rosey has remained a happy, friendly, lovable dog who has withstood long periods of convalescing with good grace.   She is that good a dog and all of us at FFFR love her dearly :)

To adopt Rosey, please fill out the form at our website -https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
My name is Gidget

I arrived at PATCH Rescue November 20, 2018 after spending time in Hesperia Animal Control and being picked up off the mean streets of Hesperia, CA.

I was born approximately November 7, 2012

I am approximately 56 pounds

Unfortunately, we are not seeking a permanent foster for Gidget. Gidget has cancer and it is keep her comfortable until we have to make that HORRIBLE call!

I LOVE to play but NOT by myself, I want you to play with me furever! I will play so long and hard, my toe nails bleed, so be careful to play on soft surface and stop playing with me to let me catch my breath! I am pretty good about potty training, as long as you are diligent. Crate trained, although I LOVE to sit with you, snuggle with you and will sleep just fine in your bed, next to you in a dog bed, etc...I am protective of my person and will bark fiercely at people entering the house. I do pretty well with other big dogs, caution with little dogs. As long as another dog does not challenge me, I am usually just vocal about my displeasure of another dog getting close to my person or food. Will you provide the furever home, I so richly deserve?!

Adoption fee includes: fixed, up to date on core vaccines (5 in 1, bordetella & rabies), dewormed, microchipped, growth tested & removed from paw and any health issues we were aware of addressed.

If Interested PLEASE contact PATCH Rescue Inc. patchrescue@gmail.com or (760) 706-0728

Adopt a Pet Listings =

https://www.adoptapet.com/adoption_rescue/93645-patch-rescue-inc-victorville-california

PetFinder Listings =

https://www.petfinder.com/member/us/ca/victorville/patch-rescue-inc-ca2487/

Adoption process is verbal interview to determine if we think your family is the right situation for the fur kid you are interested in, application (can be downloaded here: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/0B9ZDmKaRLnYfbDZLbDN5Y3hYeWM?usp=sharing), once application is reviewed and approved home check. Then we say you are becoming part of the PATCH family adopting one of our fur kids, so we expect follow up on our family member throughout their life!

Please keep in mind we are 100% volunteer run We do not have a facility, completely foster based, so we all have our real jobs, it could take 24 to 48 hours to receive a response.

Thank you for considering adoption to save two lives!

animal.description:
Nina is an active 2yo 45lb border collie/german shepherd mix. She has a lot of personality and can be a total derp (tongue hanging out sideways and everything)! She's housebroken and crate trained, and walks amazing on the leash! She loves other dogs and is good with indoor cats. She is pretty high energy and enjoys going on hikes and playing with her canine siblings. She MUST go to a home where there is a resident confident adult medium-large dog (she worships the male german shepherd in her foster home but is best friends with a female Doberman the same age.. she's fine with small dogs but she's a bit too rambunctious for them). She has also discovered the comforts of the couch and loves to lay along the top and get petted while you watch movies. Because she can still be skittish with people though, she should NOT go to a home with children or apartment living (no exceptions!). She would do best in a gentle, quiet adult only home with another dog and a house with fenced yard. She has gained a lot of skills and confidence while in her foster home, but she is ready for the next chapter in her life with a new family that will continue to help her grow.

Here is Nina's story video: https://youtu.be/KxWGwurZVWk

King is Nina's companion/emotional support dog. He's a 7-8yo purebred 75lb German Shepherd. Nina WORSHIPS him and is his shadow, follows him everywhere, and they even crate together. King is a mellow boy who prefers lounging in the house or on the couch. He would do best in a cat-free home.

They are not for first time dog owner, but when together they're pretty easy. All they need is a couch and a yard.

Adoption fee for the two together will be $550.

Nina can also be adopted by herself without King, however, we are requiring she go to a home that has another resident dog, and that she goes with a pal pup (either King or another known friend) for the first week during the transition phase, so that she doesn't panic in a new home.
Please contact Diana at (510) 333-4420 or theperfectdogrescue@gmail.com or fill out the adoption application:
http://www.theperfectdog.org/TPDadoptapp.doc

animal.description:
Brooklyn is looking for a true fairytale ending! She was a very loved puppy until her owner passed away when she was about 6-7 months old. His vet kindly took her in and hoped to find her a home quickly. Unfortunately being in the kennel environment was stressful for her and she became nervous around strangers. The vet hospital decided it may be too risky to adopt her out considering her breed and how fearful she was of someone who had come to meet her. 

For nine years she lived in the vet hospital because there was nowhere else for her to go. The staff there loved her, but it was not a home. When she turned 10 they asked us if we would consider accepting her into our rescue to live the rest of her life here with us. We agreed, and expected her to be aggressive or anxious. The dog we met, however, was none of the above. 

It seems Brooklyn spent almost a decade of her life in a kennel run because she was misunderstood. She is not an aggressive dog, she is a nervous dog. Anyone who meets her and lets her approach them at her own pace will have a loyal and honest friend for life. She never forgets her people, and she loves them fiercely. Brooklyn also loves other dogs and is happy to coexist or even run around with the youngsters. You'd be surprised at how fast this old lady can run when she gets going! 

What Brooklyn needs is a loving and understanding home who will get to know her slowly and not push her to get to know strangers too quickly once she is home. She also needs a patient home, as she has spent almost all of her life in a kennel run, never being properly housebroken. She has made some progress with this, but it will definitely be a process to completely housebreak her in a home environment. 

Brooklyn needs someone willing to give her the time to get used to them and warm up to them before they ask anything of her. She's spent a lot of her life being scared and she's still extremely wary of strangers.

We know this is a lot to ask of an adopter especially considering how difficult it can be to find adopters for senior bully breeds, but she is worth it. If she stays with us for life, that is absolutely fine, but we want to give her the shot to have a loving, and forever home with a family for the first time in her life.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Russo is a really cute little guy who loves treats but tries to limit himself to one a day so that he doesn't end up looking like a sausage. He also like peanut butter, fetch, car rides, and smelling feet. He knows the sit, stay, come, no, down, and off commands. If he doesn't see you, he'll bark at the door until you let him out. He weighs 13 pounds and is moderately active. He enjoys tugging, toys, and going for walksespecially if there are some feet somewhere to smell! He's a suburb watch dog and very protective of his home inside and out and his human. No one will ever sneak up on you because he will bark until they leave, even a dog much, much bigger than he is. He has no fears. He's very possessive of his food and his things. Even though he is friendly with other dogs and children outside the home, if they are inside it is a different story: he has to protect his 'stuff' and no dog or kid had better come near him. Older kids may be ok as long as they respect what's his. He totally won't tolerate living with a cat or a bird. It just needs to be you and him and he wants to be where you are. He can be a bit of a loner but a more loyal companion you'll never find.Russo would do best as an only pet in a home with no children. If you are looking for a loyal best friend who would watch over you and your property, please fill out an adoption application for him. He's a good boy a bit set in his ways who deserves a good home!

animal.description:
Adoption Fee: $200
Fostered in Texas
Age: 9 years
Weight: 18 lbs.

6/15/20 - Cash began feeling ill this weekend. His foster mom took him to the Emergency Clinic today and he was found to have anemia, infection of unknown origin and elevated liver enzymes. Also elevated bile acids. He is being referred to Internal Med Specialist for ultrasound of his liver. We will update as we know more.

6/7/19 - Hi, my name is Cash and I'm from Texas.  Yep,  a Texas sized Yorkie with a Texas sized bark.  Still a lover though.  You kind of have to hear my bark to believe it is coming out of this little body.  I think someone mixed a little raspy doberman in my vocal cords.  So, don't expect any cute Tinkerbell tunes to be coming out of this body.  Speaking of my body, since I'm getting a little up in age, I was having some trouble at night when I was sleeping with wetting myself.  It was so embarrassing and all the other dogs would just get up and move away from me.  I talked to foster mom about it and she and the vet started me on something called Proin and now I wake as dry as the Sahara Desert.  Whew!  No more getting made fun of.   

2/10/19 - Hi, my name is Cash and I'm from Texas.  Yep,  a Texas sized Yorkie with a Texas sized bark.  Still a lover though.  You kind of have to hear my bark to believe it is coming out of this little body.  I think someone mixed a little raspy doberman in my vocal cords.  So, don't expect any cute Tinkerbell tunes to be coming out of this body.  Speaking of my body, since I'm getting a little up in age, I was having some trouble at night when I was sleeping with wetting myself.  It was so embarrassing and all the other dogs would just get up and move away from me.  I talked to foster mom about it and she and the vet started me on something called Proin and now I wake as dry as the Sahara Desert.  Whew!  No more getting made fun of.  Oh, one other thing the vet and foster mom talked about was that I seemed to be blinking alot and the vet said that I have dry eye.  Guess that Proin REALLY WORKS!  lol  No, it doesn't really affect the eyes, but I do have to let foster mom put some drops in my eyes (Cyclosporin drops)  daily to help with the dryness.  So, if you give me my daily pill, I will stay dry on one end during the night and give me my daily eye drops, I will stay moist on the other end and then I am one happy Yorkie/Raspy Doberman mix.  

12/16/18 - Cash is a "diamond in the ruff".  When he was originally picked up, he was covered in fleas and his hair was terribly matted.  He was shaved down and had pretty rough looking skin.  His skin has improved and he is looking to much better. Just wait until his hair grows back in!  :)

Cash had his surgery to remove the bladder stones on 11.27.18 and has recovered well from that surgery.  He is now on a prescription diet to hopefully prevent further stone formation.  We are still waiting on the report on the type of bladder stones. He had a bladder infection that was cleared with antibiotics.  He is having some issues with occasional nighttime incontinence so we are working to figure out the cause of that.  He wears a belly band and does not seem bothered by it at all.  

Cash is a very pleasant pup who gets along well with his foster siblings.  He loves to snuggle in bed at night with his foster mom and other pups. 

11/26/2018 - Cash was given away online to a lady who ended up taking him to a vet only to find out that she could not afford him due to all of his presenting medical needs. She reached out to us since he needed immediate surgery. He also has flea dermatitis and dry eye. She told us he was covered with fleas when she got him. She treated him for the fleas and did get some meds for him and also medicated shampoo for his horribly irritated skin. 

He is presently at our vet being prepped for surgery. As we know more about Cash we will update his bio.

animal.description:
Sammie

LOVES to take "Selfies"
11-13 years old
Sheltie and Cattle dog mix
You would never know his age by his energy level and zest for life.
Fully vetted
Dog friendly
Cat friendly
Would likely be fine around kids (current foster doesn't have any)
Loves a cozy sweater or fashionable shirt
House trained
Kennel trained and knows some basic commands

Does great off leash once he knows the boundaries and we're his home Is
Bonded with his sister Buster 
He was seriously borderline feral and now he loves a good Netflix marathon. 
28lbs

Sammie belonged to an older gentleman with his brother and sister. They lived in an abandoned trailer in Bridgeport. Their owner will never be able to return home and this is his last wish to make sure his dogs are safe and loved for the remainder of their lives. At one point they were inside/outside dogs however since their owners health started to decline they had been "on their own" so to speak and were able to go in and out of a mobile home. We trapped all 3 and Sammie, who was the most feral was the first to trap. Sammie is now 100% inside house dog adjusted. He is house trained, crate trained, knows some commands and is just living his best life. Sammie actually played a crucial role in the rescue of both his brother Bear, (who has been adopted), and his sister Buster who is still looking for a perfect home. Sammie is a sweet boy who is looking for a home, with his sister Buster. 

Sammie is bonded (healthy bond) with his more shy sister Buster and she really follows his lead. We would love them to find a foster or FURever home of their own, hopefully with less dogs than their current foster. The home needs to be ok being patient and showing them the love they need to continue to progress towards their potential awesomeness! Sammie and Buster are good with other dogs and cats, however both do better with other more submissive and or independent canine housemates.

This pair is truly beyond deserving and so amazing. After losing their human, being left to basically fend for themselves, being trapped, being mostly rehabbed and now living in a foster with so many other dogs. This dynamic duo deserves a fantastic home to live out the rest of their time on this planet. 

BONDED WITH SAMMIE, MUST GO TOGETHER

Due to having them so long in rescue and truly wanting to find them the most amazing home we have lowered their fee, as long as they are adopted together.

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

If you think Buster and Sammie may be a good fit for your household and you're interested in helping please contact us!!! 

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
I'm Tatiana! Some of you may know me as one of the wiggliest and happiest gals out here at Mackenzie's. While that's totally accurate, some of you might have heard about me from national newspapers. I don't want to get into it too much since my life is night and day different from what it had been, but I'd been beaten pretty badly and abandoned in the woods. I was saved by a kind person, and made my way to Mackenzie's. 

Thanks to tons of love and support from so many generous, kind, and patient people, I've healed quite a bit and made great strides...and I think I'm ready to find my "forever home." At Mackenzie's, I've grown to love the staff and volunteers, and I'm spoiled with long walks, play time in the big yard... In the summer, I love to splash around in the water! I'll even play a little fetch sometimes. I have a signature wiggle that is known around the grounds - it makes its appearance when I see one of my favorite people! 

Because of my past, I really would be happiest as the only pet in a quiet home with love and cuddles galore. I've come such a long way, and can't wait to share all that I've learned and all my love with the right person. 

Birthday: 01-09-2010

Meet-Your-Match Canineality Color is: Orange Goofball! 

Mackenzie's Animal Sanctuary is the Midwest's largest no-kill dog sanctuary. As such, Mackenzie's is 'a home along the way,' providing our dogs with excellent and individualized care in all areas (medical and otherwise) and tending to whatever special needs a dog may have. Some of our dogs have special behavioral needs (like fear issues) and will need to build a relationship with the adopter before going to their forever home. 
For safety's sake, we are looking for homes with physical fenced-in areas. 
Please fill out our online adoption survey at www.mackenzies.info

animal.description:
Zoey came to us back in November of 2017 with her pups. They have long since been adopted, but Zoey has had difficulty finding a family.  Luckily, we have been able to learn about her personality and needs through various temporary foster homes which has proven very valuable and we feel that, with the knowledge we now have, we can truly help Zoey and her family find each other.  

Here’s what we know about Zoey:  She is an approximately 4 year old PitBull Terrier weighing around 50 pounds.  She does well with other dogs on her terms. She prefers a home where she can have her own area to “get away to” be left alone when things get too overwhelming (too loud, too many people, etc).  So a home without too much going on might be best for her. 

She does well with kids, but because she sometimes wants to be alone, we feel like living in a home with kids might overwhelm her, therefore we do not wish to place her in a home with children.  

Zoey will need an experienced dog owner, preferably someone with Pitbull or other stubborn breed experience.  She can be an absolute joy to be around, however she has a stubborn streak in her.

We feel that she would love to go on hikes and explore new places with her family.  Or maybe a nice leash walk followed by snuggles on the couch?  Maybe even some swimming or a nice car ride?  Zoey loves doing it all!  

If you think you might be the family Zoey needs, fill out an adoption application at the link below.
https://forms.gle/gw9k5r2ArJwJyVm87
  Feel free to message us with questions regarding Zoey.  

Zoey doesn’t understand why her family hasn’t come for her yet and why she never gets “chosen”.  Please help us give Zoey the happiness she deserves by finding her perfect family that we know is out there somewhere. She is currently been here the longest of any animal in the rescue

animal.description: Brad Pit was found roaming the neighborhood of one of our previous adopters and volunteers and was in terrible condition.  He rallied his fellow neighbors and they took up a collection to get him to a vet to evaluate his condition.  He was diagnosed with advanced heartworm disease infection, his belly was swollen due to fluid build up from the strain on his heart and his condition was critical.  The good news was, his blood work was really good.  So, the vet felt there was a good chance he could survive this.  He was put on Vetmedin (a medication to help lessen the stress on his heart).   Once the fluid reduced we saw how severely malnourished and thin he was. We have fattened him up & his heart condition has improved tremendously and is now off of his heart medication!  His heartworm status is now moderately positive.  He was recently cleared to be neutered and came through the surgery like a star!  Brad Pit is such a sweet and happy guy.  You can see in his eyes this boy has a will to live! The next step is heartworm treatment to completely rid him of those nasty heartworms, but we would love to find a quiet foster home for him while he undergoes heartworm treatment.  Please contact us if you are interested in fostering this guy for a couple of months.  He's so wonderful, you might just end up keeping him!  Thank you!

animal.description:
Gretel is a three old female Chihuahua/Dachshund mix who weighs about 20lbs. She is up to date on vaccines and spayed. Gretel is crate trained, but still working on house training. She is good with other dogs, she does have a prey drive so we wouldn't put her in a home with birds or pet rodents.

Gretel is very shy around humans and takes quite a while to trust humans. She needs a family that understands that it could take months for her to trust them enough to even approach them voluntarily and is willing to give her that time. Gretel has never shown a hint of aggression, but would be overwhelmed by children. Because it will take some time for her to trust someone enough to let them leash her, Gretel needs to be in a home with a fence and would not do well in an apartment setting.

Before applying for Gretel, please carefully consider if you are willing to have the patience it will take for Gretel to be comfortable and put in the work. We are not exaggerating - expect it to take MONTHS for her to trust you. She will spend most of that time hiding under the furniture. When Gretel does decide to trust, she is very sweet and cuddly with her person. However, this a dog that will always hide when you have visitors. She will likely never come out of her shell enough to enjoy the dog park, breweries or anything that requires being around strange people. Gretel needs someone who understands her limits and is willing to love her as she is. Gretel is going to be work, but she's worth the effort.

If you are interested in adopting Gretel please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte is responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

animal.description:
Meet Oscar 
This boy has our hearts and they’re breaking in pieces that he has yet to find his forever loving home.  After two false starts and much abuse and neglect, Oscar is safe and loved with us. But a shelter is no place to live out your life. Especially when you are has wonderful and friendly a boy as Oscar. Every day Oscar hopes that today will be the day. He LOVES people and he so wants to be that special boy in someone’s life. 
Oscar is nearly seven now. Between his breed, he’s an American bull terrier mix, and his age, no one has been willing to give him a chance. But they should. He is something special and we’re not just saying that. Oscar LOVES with his whole heart. He absolutely adores people and children. He’s trained, he’s calm, he’s gentle, he’s affectionate, he’s goofy and he’s incredibly loyal. Oscar welcomes a good back scratch and wags his whole body when he sees his people. He’s the kind of boy that you’ll want to while away the day with on the couch or porch or going for a drive. Oscar loves going for drives. He loves walking and makes strolling easy to do. He’s exceptionally companionable. 
Oscar has been given a special bed in his kennel, with his very own pillow made just for him. He loves his bed and can often be found on it, quietly chewing a bone or snoozing his day away. He has touched many hearts and has a guardian who sends him monthly care packages.  While on one hand we’re glad to see he’s seemingly content, on the other we wish he would be doing this in someone’s home and brightening their day. 
Despite Oscar’s past, Oscar has a heart of gold when it comes to people.  He LOVES people and is kind and gentle with children.  Oscar has had a tough past with other dogs and needs to be an only dog. He doesn’t like cats, squirrels or deer and will give chase. He’s incredibly smart and knows basic commands. He loves the water and enjoys bathing in his kiddie pool. His tail is always wagging and he gives those he loves big sloppy kisses. The family or person able and willing to open their heart and home to Oscar will be richly rewarded with one incredible dog. We hope that special someone will come for Oscar so he can make his/her day that much brighter. 
If interested in Oscar, please submit an application online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy., Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
PLEASE CONTACT MY FOSTER MOM AT 703-967-1000 FOR MORE INFORMATION...THANK YOU!

My name is Edgar and I was found wandering the streets in rural Virginia.  I was taken in at a shelter where they cleaned me up and neutered me.  I don't remember when I was born - I may be around 6 years old but sometimes I play like I'm still a pup.  

Although my color is more golden, my personality is all Pyr.  I display the true guarding ability of the Pyr.  Since I have no livestock to guard, I feel responsible to guard my family.   I am very loving with my family and will be very protective.  Because of my guarding, I'd prefer go with someone that is very familiar with Pyrs and no children.  

Check out my professional photo...aren't I handsome?  I know how to sit and give a paw or two.  My favorite things?  I love to give kisses and curl up on my doggie bed.  I am treat driven and want to please. 

Once I meet a person, I begin to like them.  My foster mom and I worked hard on interactions with other dogs...so I'm doing fine with most dogs and have to admit that I like the females much better!  We haven't encountered cats yet, so we do not know about felines.

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org. There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone! 

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/

Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization. We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Meet Willow!

 4 years old, Spayed Female, Australian Cattle Dog/Great Pyrenees mix, 70 lbs

**NOTE:  Potential adopters must live locally to the Cleveland, TN area; please read complete bio

Willow is a special girl.  A very special girl, that need a very special person to adopt her.  Her preference is a woman-led home. She loves air conditioning, and comfy beds.  Also likes to defluff toys and play with them!

She is a smart girl, who can be stubborn when she wants to sleep in during the mornings (haha).  She has been in rescue the past three (3) years of her life.  She takes quite some time to warm up to new people, and does not show well in a kennel/cage (has cage aggression with strangers).  She would like to be able to be an inside/outside dog, as she enjoys doing both (especially the cool air!).  YOU MUST HAVE A FENCED IN YARD!

Willow cannot be placed in a home with other dogs or cats, as she is aggressive and will attack WITHOUT being provoked.  A securely fenced in yard is a must, but 4-foot fencing is just fine.  She knows basic commands, crate trained, and house trained.  She was adopted originally from rescue as a puppy, but eventually became too aggressive with the other dogs in her home to live there safely.  When given a chance, she loves to run around the back yard and roll down the hill!  She likes short walks in familiar quiet parks, but doesn't want to meet new people or dogs, thank you.

She has skin allergies that can become severe in the summer, and needs regular vet visits to manage this with Bravecto and ear meds, etc.  Also requires grain free food. If you can commit to giving her the loving home she deserves, she promises to love you forever. It will take several meetings to adjust to new people, so potential adopters need to live in the Cleveland/Chattanooga/Knoxville area.  Thank you!

NOTES:

Our adoption fees include spay/neuter, microchip, set of three (3) DHPP vaccines (puppies under 4 months only), bordatella (kennel cough) vaccine, rabies vaccine (over 3 months old),  heartworm test (6 months or older), deworming, and up to date flea/tick/heartworm prevention.  

This dog/puppy is in foster care in Cleveland, TN. Our standard adoption fee is $150 unless otherwise noted, which includes all vetting.  Application, vet references, personal references, and home visits may be required prior to adoption. 

Please email us at pawsofvalor.ar@gmail.com to ask questions or ask for an adoption application.

Name: Noel
Breed: American Pitbull Terrier
Age: Approx. 7-8 years old (as of Oct 2020)
Sex: Female
Good with Dogs: No 
Good with Cats: No
Good with Kids: Yes

Noel is a wonderful, squishy lovebug that loves to romp and play. She's a semi-active little gal that beams happiness from her head to her tail when she is around people! She absolutely loves treats and would eat until she pops. Noel is a true delight to be around. She lives for smooches and bellyrubs in particular. Noel is playful, gentle with people, and would make the greatest best friend!

Noel came to us after having been discarded like so much trash after what we can only assume was a failed backyard breeding run. Noel was "used" and dumped off, where a good Samaritan asked for our assistance in getting her well and finding her a loving home. Noel is a treasure of a velvet hippo that you just come away wanting more!

animal.description:
Jesse was found as a stray in Darlington. He was picked at the intersection of N Main St and Doneraile St.  He has been in foster with Debbie A and she has been trying to help him gain weight. Many of his teeth are broken. He has badly clipped ears and a lot of hair loss. Despite this, he is very affectionate and sweet.  HW+; 45lbs; 2-3 yrs old; bull mix; 11/19/18

Foster update May 28:   I picked him up from out of the road, dodging traffic, on Halloween night.  He was in terrible shape when I found him.  He had a collar on but was so emaciated, his skin was red and irritated and he was so dirty.  We began working to put some weight back on him and work on his skin issues.  He still has a little hair loss on his back, but he is doing much better.  He is an older guy and you can tell that humans have not been kind to him in his life.  Despite all that, he is the sweetest and most loving little man.  I had his intake done at the shelter and brought him straight home with me into foster, so he's not spent any time at the shelter.  Great dog so deserving of a home of his own!

animal.description:
Caroline came to us as a transfer from  another shelter a little over a year ago,   This little lady lives life large!  Probably a mix of pit bull, perhaps pug, and who knows what else, Caroline has been described as a cross between a pit bull and a stick of dynamite.   She has that much enthusiasm for everything she does!  Caroline needs to be challenged, stimulated and guided by a firm but loving owner.  When she first arrived, Caroline had no tolerance for other dogs, but has learned to accept that they can have a place on her planet when she's out and about, but never, never sharing the same home. 
On the other hand, she is incredibly social with the two legged sort, often assuming the role of Mayor, greeting everyone she meets when walking throughout the nearby village.  She just loves a  party or just good conversation and is always happy to take center stage.  
Caroline has a great sense of adventure and has a positive can do attitude! Just check out the pictures from our walks - trying out a skate board, a swing, a toy car, you name it - she'll try it!  And, it's always her idea! If something has wheels and a motor - even better!  In fact, the bigger the better! The UPS truck  was great, the heavy equipment in the parking lot was a blast, but a plain ol' car will do just fine, as long as it transports her for a new adventure! 
Caroline is not a dog for a first time dog owner, but for an experienced person who loves a dog with a strong personality, a sense of humor and a sense of adventure.  If this little pumpkin isn't well understood or challenged, she'll come up with other things to amuse her, which, you probably wouldn't find nearly as funny as she does.  For the right person, Caroline promises to be one of the most entertaining, lovable and engaging dogs you'll ever share your home with. 
This little pumpkin is between 2 - 3 years old and weighs in at just about 37 pounds (of solid muscle). 

Adoption Fee: $175  (dogs over 1 year) or $225 (dogs under 1 year) includes spay/neuter rabies, DHLPP and kennel cough vaccinations, worming, flea treatment, heartworm testing, heartworm preventative, microchipping and microchip registration fee. 

Please call us at 607-594-2255 ext. 201 to schedule an appointment to meet her. Adoption application and details on adopting can be found on our website here: http://schuylerhumane.org

My name is SAVANNAH & I'm a beautiful 2 yr F White  Amstaff/Pit X. I'm a petite 55 lbs of PURE SUGAR. I'm a gorgeous girl with sky blue eyes... shy but sweet & friendly. I'm still young so I need daily structured exercise and discipline. I know "sit" but need to learn more commands and still need help with leash training; but nothing that the proper leash/collar tools like a "gentle leader" harness won't fix. I'm currently living with other large dogs but I'm only good with the dogs I know and because I've not been socialized with other outside dogs,  I'm "socially ackward" and bark/lunge at other dogs (especially small dogs) &  would need an experienced handler to introduce me properly so it's preferred that I be a SOLO DOG. Also I'm not fond of cats so NO CATS for me. I've not been around young kids either so older kids ages 10 yrs+ would be best! I'm a sweet blue-eyed beauty and need someone who knows, appreciates and understands my breed! I will be your BFF.. come meet/adopt me today!

animal.description:
Hi meet Shelby,

Shelby is a 4 year old Boxer Pit mix. She is a sweet and loving girl who has a large personality. She loves getting pets and cuddles. Shelby is great with other dogs and people although with people she has to start off slow, she want to make sure those around her are good and are not going to hurt her but love her.
 
Shelby was living in a home for a moment but then they let her go and was rescued by a fellow rescuer. After some searching they reached out to us and we took her in. Shelby spent over a year in our hands learning and observing the world with new eyes. She is afraid of new things but learns fast and loves hard.

We hold an event every weekend at our facility on SATURDAY 11-5pm.   Please visit our social media platforms for the specifics for each weekend as it changes from week to week. Please find our application at lovejoyfoundation.org when you come to an event please bring that filled out in hand with you. You can find our application at Lovejoyfoundation.orgYou MUST submit an APPLICATION via email in hopes to get an appointment, our application is found on our website lovejoyfoundation.org. If you do not get a phone call by Friday then we did not have anything available for you or the pet of interest was adopted before we got you application. We are a Southern California based rescue and do nothing adopt further than an hour from our headquarters in Inglewood, Ca. we do not adopt out more than a 30 minute radius. We appreciate you being understanding and Patient as we attempt to go back to a new normal.

animal.description:
Morrisey

Located in Dalton NE

5ish years old 

Catahoula mix

Really would do best as an only animal

No idea on cats but to error on the side of caution we would say no

Has been good with children but also had an incident with a child 

House trained 

Doesn't love a crate but will crate, he also knows all basic commands

Fully vetted 

45lbs 

This is Morrisey and he was actually adopted 1.5 years ago ago. He was so loved and cherished in this home. He was an only dog, had grand children to play with and really we THOUGHT he was in the most amazing home. Until it wasn't. One evening a situation occured between Morrisey and one of the grand children which truly wasn't Morrisey's fault. Morrisey can be high anxiety and he was trigger stacked. The adopters at the time ignored all his VERY CLEAR communications that he was uncomfortable. We had really hoped that the adopters would have even tried to work through the issue but it became apparent they never had any intention on doing so. After they abandoned their dog in the impound vet (without any of his belongings including his BED) and surrendered their ownerhip to HPPAW they went out 3 days later, while Morrisey was still sitting sad, scared, confused and alone and bought a new puppy, and wanted to reuse the bed. It was truly heartbreaking. 

When we recieved this lug back he was moribly obese and a shell of the dog we adopted out and our hearts were immediately broke into a thousand pieces. He went back to his original foster and while he was happy to see her, she owns several dogs and also has several fosters so this amazing guy is growing more and more defeated by the day. He went from being a cherished only dog with devoted people to living in a home where he gets far less attention and is very limited to where in the house he can be when, so we understand his sadness, goodness we are sad too. No matter he still has the best little wiggling booty around and is seriously an incredibly sweet soul. Over the past 1.5 years he has lost weight and is at an appropriate weight. He has again learned to love rides in the car, he's learned how to trust people again and he REALLY needs a home, temporary or permanent ASAP.

We would really love to find a home for him where he is an only dog, he has previously lived in a foster with multiple other dogs but it's an incredibly experienced foster who did super slow introductions. While he has actually spent time daily with children for months, due to the 1 incident, which wasn't his fault, we are looking for a home with limited children. We want him to go to a home thats excited to work with him as he's super eager to please. He will try to push his luck and get away with things so someone who is willing to lovingly correct him and understands we give dogs boundaries BECAUSE we love them would be awesome. We really want somewhere that he will be protected and loved. Where he can relax and feel safe. He does love people and truly LOVES rides in the pick up so he may be a great companion for a trucker looking for a canine partner for adventures! 

If you think that Morrisey may be a match for you please contact us ASAP! 

Morrisey has been waiting such a long time and really deserves a foster with less dogs or a fantastic FURever home!

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application at bigdogrescueproject.org/adopt.

Our adoption fee includes age appropriate vaccinations, deworming, microchipping and transport expenses. 

Grace is adoptable to homes in WA, OR, or TX.

Grace is a 2 year old lab mix weighing around 40 pounds. She showed up on her foster's property severely underweight. She is very small for a lab and while she has been putting on weight, we don't think she will ever reach 50 pounds. Grace gets along well with male large dogs and is high energy especially when playing. She is crate trained, walks well on a leash, has a very sweet disposition, and likes a lot of attention. We think she would do well with children over age 13. We have no knowledge of how she would be around cats or livestock.

Grace would do best in a dog savvy household that can help her continue to learn manners and harness her high energy. She would do best as an only dog or with a med/large male dog. She would not be best suited for a home with a female dog, small dogs, or cats.

All children at home should be at least age 5 to be approved for adoption!
Pacific Northwest adoption fee is $450 to help offset travel and medical expenses.

~ THIS IS A COURTESY POST ~ PLZ DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS ~
To adopt this dog Please call 508-586-2053 Tues, and Thurs through Sun: 1-4pm or email info@apcsm.org for adoption information. Be sure to tell them ARK sent you! #ARKforCupid

 Cupid is an almost 3-year old, 50+-pound lab mix female located in Brockton, MA. She is very friendly as shelter staff and volunteers can testify! She is so sweet and precious, she gives great hugs, and her eyes are most expressive. 

A message from Cupid:
Hi ARK Friends! It’s Cupid, again. That’s right, I am back but I promise it’s not my fault! If you remember, I lived at the Animal Protection Center of Southern Massachusetts for a long, long time, but landed a long-term foster gig early this year. I really liked it there and was a good girl (mostly, hey nobody’s perfect!), but the nice man has a tough work schedule. We learned that I need an environment that is more stable and consistent. So I am back where my old buddies are taking me on field trips, play dates, and pack walks as much as they can. Still, I would love to be adopted for realz this time.

I’m a very smart dog who loves learning new things and solving problems. I enjoy any type of food puzzle. Seems like I can find a treat anywhere, so I’m thinking of taking up scent work in my spare time. (I have a cute nose by the way!) You can hide treats all over the yard or house for me. Let’s browse for DIY dog-friendly activities, too! 

I am best-suited for a small, active family that’s outgoing and would enjoy being outdoors with me. All of my favorite things involve the outdoors, such as hiking, walking, and swimming. I am not suited for young kids, but teens who can help with consistency would be fun to play with. Now, as far as fur-siblings, it’ll take a while for a symbiotic relationship, you’ll just have to watch over me until I am used to things. I am ok around horses, but no cats or rabbits for me! 

My foster dad likened me to a toddler that you need to watch and be one step ahead of at all times. Truth be told I can be a handful and harbor puppy tendencies. He’ll also tell you I had to brush up on my house-training skills. I am my best with a routine and consistency. Please call or email to meet me!  508-586-2053, info@apcsm.org
Love, Cupid xo

animal.description:
Squash is just adorable. He was adopted in January 2019 and was recently returned to us. He has neurological issues and general fear/anxiety. When he was adopted he had 1 seizure, but we don't know much about his medical history in the last year and a half. Unfortunately, he does have some neurological issues that affect his hind legs. Squash may walk a little funny, but he can walk and run like any other dog. He would not do well in a home with small children or a lot of activity. He takes a long time to warm up to new people and places so his forever family will need to be very patient. 

We rescued Squash and his momma, Raddish, from Animal Control. Their owner had too many dogs and could no longer care for them, so she surrendered them. Squash was in a foster home when he was first rescued in 2018 and they told us, "He is super affectionate and wants to be in the middle of any cuddle pile. He gets really bouncy when he’s excited. He loves to jump in my lap to get some love from me and my dog Lady. I think he would be in heaven in a home with other energetic and affectionate dogs."  What a sweet boy! Squash's date of birth is 11/7/2017 and he weighs about 25 pounds.

Squash has been neutered, is current on all vaccines, is on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, is microchipped, and comes with a 30 day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required. Visit fayettefcar.com to submit an application.

animal.description:
Mama T was brought in as an owner surrender. The owner could no longer take care of her. She is a little skittish but she warms up quickly.  HW+; 38lbs; 1-2 yrs old; lab mix; 8/27/18

Safe- HAL

Update Oct 16:  Mama T had 7 puppies.  Tragically all  7 of them did not make it.  The vet feels they had not been alive inside for some time now.  Not clear why they all died. 

Foster Update Nov 10: She’s good with other dogs after she warms up to them. Loves to cuddle, crate trained, potty trained, and great on a leash. She does stay close by without a leash also.


Update April 25: Mama T has a sad story to tell but still a joyful outlook. She came to the shelter when her owner was no longer able to care for her. She was pregnant with 7 puppies but sadly none of the 7 survived. Mama T hasn't let the loss of her puppies dim her sunny disposition though, she remains friendly and social with other dogs and especially loves getting love and attention from her person. She is a nice smaller size and packs a lot of love in a little package! She is a champion cuddler and walks wonderfully on a leash. Mama T has so much love to give to one very special person.  She is very affectionate and bonds with her person and thinks it is her job to be a protector.  Because of this instinct, we are recommending that she go into a one person home with someone who would appreciate a dog who wants to be their guardian and keep them safe. Mama T will make a wonderful companion for the right person. She is also crate trained and spent some time in a foster home where we discovered she was house trained as well. Mama T had her cat test and when she was walked by the cattery she didn't react to the kitties at all. This little love bug has waited for a forever home that will cherish her and treat her with love and the value every pet deserves. Let her spread a little of her love into your home, we think you'll never regret it!

animal.description:
(Version française disponible ici:  

https://www.sitwithme.ca/fr/dogs/macaroon/)

Macaroon

American Pit Bull Terrier mix

Female

6 years old

**Due to her breed label, she needs a home in an area that does not have restrictions on pit bull type dogs.  This means she must find her home outside of Ontario.

Dogs: She does do well with calmer dogs and can make friends, but needs slow and supervised introductions.  She would be quite happy as an only dog.

Cats: No, thank you.

Kids: No, thank you, only because she would prefer a calmer home life.

Housing Type: Detached

Fenced in yard: Required

Special Note: Macaroon is unsure shy when meeting new people but is easily managed for success with treats and kindness and must be given the ability to approach when she is ready (which is usually quite quickly and with gusto!).


Meet Mac.  Mac is a beautiful girl ready to provide all of the drive by and bonking kisses you could ever want!  She adores her people and even making friends with even more people.  You see, she sees people as wonderful cuddling partners and just can’t stand not giving out and kisses and cuddles like candy to kids on Halloween!   Mac knows a few impressive commands like sit, down, leave it and gentle and hopes that her new person would consider taking her to training classes or teaching her more as she is a fan of treats and praise too!

Mac is house and crate trained.  She is considered a low to medium energy girl and one walk a day and some play interaction with her people is enough to keep her very happy.  She is able to have dog friends but needs slow introductions as her first instinct is to not be fond of other dogs.  When Mac is in her crate, she will bark and so is not ideal in attached housing.  Speaking of barking, Mac is also a talker in play and will talk to you with grumbles and silly noises.  She’s a bit of a clown sometimes and shows you both a goofy and sweet side.

When meeting new people, as described above, Mac can seem shy.  This means she will needs some guidance to make sure interactions with people are always positive.  Forcing her into stranger situations, or living in a busy household (a home with new visitors weekly, for instance) might be too much action for Mac.  Once she knows someone, she certainly will shower them with love next time she sees them too.

If Mac sounds like the gal for you, please complete our online application: http://www.sitwithme.ca/dogs/macaroon
